Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rain tapered off across Hart County throughout the afternoon of the 6th, runoff from the day's excessive rainfall resulted in high water conditions persisting, with many roads remaining closed through the evening hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across portions of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area, mainly to the southeast of Phoenix, during the afternoon hours on September 8th. Some of the stronger storms produced gusty and damaging winds that approached 60 mph in strength. The strong winds downed multiple trees in the community of Gilbert, just to the southwest of Mesa-Gateway Airport. Small to moderate hailstones were also reported; at roughly 1700MST there was a report of hailstones about 0.88 inches in diameter near the intersection of Power and Germann Roads. There were no reports of injury due to the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with gusty and damaging outflow winds developed to the southeast of Phoenix during late afternoon hours on September 8th. Some of the stronger storms affected communities such as Higley. At 1710MST a trained spotter located about 2 miles  southeast of Higley reported that outflow winds estimated to be as high as 60 mph downed multiple trees along Germann Road between Greenfield and Power Roads. There were no reports of injury due to the falling trees.

According to a report from the public, at 1705MST gusty outflow winds estimated to be as high as 60 mph downed some trees about 2 miles to the southwest of the Phoenix Mesa-Gateway Airport. The report was obtained via social media. There were no reports of any injuries due to the falling trees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure over the western United States allowed for high temperatures to top out nearly 10 degrees above normal at the end of the month. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, two heat-associated fatalities occurred during this time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One heat-associated fatality was reported by the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, with their details, such as age, gender, circumstances and location unavailable.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold high pressure system arriving from the north, coinciding with the approach of a mid and upper level trough from the west allowed for winter weather to develop over central North Carolina.  As precipitation developed during the day on February 20, colder air continued to be advected into North Carolina courtesy of strong high pressure located over the Great Lakes. A brief mixture of rain and snow changed to snow as the precipitation spread east throughout central NC during the late afternoon and early evening. Temperatures were near or slightly above freezing during the late afternoon, limiting accumulations. Temperatures fell below freezing during the evening and the snow accumulated rapidly. By late evening, light snow was falling over much of central North Carolina. The snow ended shortly after midnight at most locations. Storm total snowfall amounts ranged between one and four inches, with most Triad and Triangle locations receiving between two and three inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from 1 inches across southwestern portions of the county to 3 inches across northeastern portions of the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moisture overspreading a southward-moving cold front resulted in development of precipitation across the North Carolina mountains throughout the daylight hours of the 21st. Temperatures were cold enough in most locations for this precipitation to fall as snow, although rain mixed in at times below about 2500 feet. By the time the snow tapered off during the evening, snowfall totals ranged from trace amounts up to an inch in the lower interior valleys, to 1 to 4 inches above 2500 feet and in the valleys near the Blue Ridge.

A vigorous upper-level low pressure center moved east from southern Colorado across south central Kansas through the late afternoon on Tuesday, June 9, 2020. As it did, a surface low deepened and moved east across Kansas pushing a cold front south across the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles before moving into western Texas. The cold front moved into the Oklahoma Panhandle early in the morning and quickly swept south through through the Texas Panhandle, continuing to move across the region. A strong pressure gradient between the low over Kansas and high pressure surging southeast out of Colorado created very strong winds across the Texas and Oklahoma Panhandles behind the front, which lasted into the early evening.||Across the northern half of the Texas Panhandle, sustained winds increased into the 40 to greater than 50 MPH range out of the north to northwest, with gusts mainly in the 55 to 65 MPH range. Farther south, sustained winds generally ranged from 37 to 46 MPH with gusts mainly in the 50 to 60 MPH range. These strong winds lasted most of the day before finally diminishing from west to east beginning in the late afternoon. Although the relative humidity was only 15 to 35 percent across the northwestern two-thirds of the Texas Panhandle, the high winds and dry fuels associated with recent onset of moderate to extreme drought in the area led to a high wildfire danger across part of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The West Texas Mesonet station 12 miles southwest of Claude measured sustained winds in the 40 to 42 MPH range during this time period. The highest sustained wind of 42 MPH occurred at 1509CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early morning storm produced hail in the central Oklahoma Panhandle. During the late afternoon, a moist airmass became very unstable, leading to the development of scattered thunderstorms. There were reports of large hail in the eastern Oklahoma Panhandle during the early evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A swath of nickel size hail fell from 3 miles south of Beaver into Beaver.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail fell in Beaver.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist, moderately unstable airmass and weak to moderate wind shear supported the development of scattered late afternoon and evening thunderstorms as an upper level disturbance moved across the area from the west-northwest. There were a few reports of hail in the northeast Texas Panhandle during the early evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell at Follett.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance crossing the southern Appalachians resulted in redevelopment of snow showers across the North Carolina mountains throughout the 28th and early on the 29th. The relatively long duration of the event along with the enhanced lift from the disturbance allowed for higher accumulations than normally seen during northwest flow events, while accumulating snowfall was also reported well south and east of the usual Tennessee border areas, including across portions of the middle and upper French Broad Valley. Total amounts were generally in the 2-4 inch range, although amounts as high as 8 inches were reported on some of the high peaks and ridge tops.

Moisture overspreading a southward-moving cold front resulted in development of precipitation across the North Carolina mountains throughout the daylight hours of the 21st. Temperatures were cold enough in most locations for this precipitation to fall as snow, although rain mixed in at times below about 2500 feet. By the time the snow tapered off during the evening, snowfall totals ranged from trace amounts up to an inch in the lower interior valleys, to 1 to 4 inches above 2500 feet and in the valleys near the Blue Ridge.

Behind the front very strong southwesterly winds overspread the region causing power outages and damage across central North Carolina.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and power lines were reported down across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A confluent trough developed across the Northern Plains and locked in the cold air which had pushed southward and produced numerous record low maximum and minimum temperatures.  As an extended period of warm advection and frontogenesis intensified during the afternoon of October 24, a broad area of snowfall developed, with periods of moderate to briefly heavy snowfall during the morning and early afternoon of October 25. Numerous snowfall records were established on October 24th and 25th to go along with the record cold temperatures, which also propelled the month into the top 3 snowiest Octobers at Brookings, Flandreau, Marshall, Minneota, Tracy and Yankton (1st), Windom and De Smet (2nd), and Sibley, Sanborn and Pipestone (3rd).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A long duration snowfall totaled 5.0 inches at Wessington Springs.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnant circulation from tropical storm Cristobal combined with strong, negatively tilted phasing shortwave disturbance moved across the area providing strong synoptic winds ahead of the storms. Strong, dynamic cold front initiated storms just after the noon hour with damaging winds, hail, and heavy rain observed during the afternoon. Strong post frontal drying within fierce mid level dry intrusion yielded 40 to 60 mph wind gusts and blowing dust late afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotter estimated 60 mph gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NWS storm survey found a tornado that began in southeast Cleveland County moved into Gaston County in the Crowders Mountain State Park area. Numerous snapped trees were found as the tornado moved east crossing Pinnacle Rd and Sparrow Springs Rd. The damage ended near Freedom Mill Rd with snapped and broken large branches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moisture overspreading a southward-moving cold front resulted in development of precipitation across the northeast Georgia mountains throughout the daylight hours of the 21st. Temperatures were cold enough in most locations for this precipitation to fall as snow, although rain mixed in at times below about 2000 feet. By the time the snow tapered off during the evening, snowfall totals ranged from trace amounts up to an inch in the lower interior valleys, to 1 to 4 inches above 2000 feet and in the valleys near the Blue Ridge.

Precipitation developed across the northwest Piedmont during the afternoon and early evening in association with a developing coastal low pressure system. Precip began as rain in most areas, but transitioned to snow fairly quickly. A warm ground and rain mixing in undercut the accumulation potential significantly, but total snowfall of around an inch was reported by early evening.

Precipitation developed across the northwest Piedmont during the afternoon and early evening in association with a developing coastal low pressure system. Precip began as rain in most areas, but transitioned to snow fairly quickly. A warm ground and rain mixing in undercut the accumulation potential significantly, but total snowfall of around an inch was reported by early evening.

A potent pref-frontal squall line crossed the local forecast area during the late afternoon across SE Georgia and continuing eastward exiting the NE Florida Atlantic coast through midnight.  There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees and power lines were blown down across the county. No reports of major damage to homes.

A vigorous upper-level low pressure center moved east from southern Colorado across south central Kansas through the late afternoon on Tuesday, June 9, 2020. As it did, a surface low deepened and moved east across Kansas pushing a cold front south across the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles before moving into western Texas. The cold front moved into the Oklahoma Panhandle early in the morning and quickly swept south through through the Texas Panhandle, continuing to move across the region. A strong pressure gradient between the low over Kansas and high pressure surging southeast out of Colorado created very strong winds across the Texas and Oklahoma Panhandles behind the front, which lasted into the early evening.||Across the northern half of the Texas Panhandle, sustained winds increased into the 40 to greater than 50 MPH range out of the north to northwest, with gusts mainly in the 55 to 65 MPH range. Farther south, sustained winds generally ranged from 37 to 46 MPH with gusts mainly in the 50 to 60 MPH range. These strong winds lasted most of the day before finally diminishing from west to east beginning in the late afternoon. Although the relative humidity was only 15 to 35 percent across the northwestern two-thirds of the Texas Panhandle, the high winds and dry fuels associated with recent onset of moderate to extreme drought in the area led to a high wildfire danger across part of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 50 mph wind gust was measured at Hutchinson County Airport, located 2 miles north of Borger.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weakening area of precipitation associated with developing low pressure along the Gulf Coast overspread northeast Georgia during the morning. Temperatures were cold enough in most areas for the precipitation to fall, or at least begin as snow. While heavy snow accumulated in areas roughly along and north of I-85, total accumulations of 1 to 2 inches were seen for a couple of tier of counties south of there. Due to a warm ground and roads, travel problems were minimal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnant circulation from tropical storm Cristobal combined with strong, negatively tilted phasing shortwave disturbance moved across the area providing strong synoptic winds ahead of the storms. Strong, dynamic cold front initiated storms just after the noon hour with damaging winds, hail, and heavy rain observed during the afternoon. Strong post frontal drying within fierce mid level dry intrusion yielded 40 to 60 mph wind gusts and blowing dust late afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotter estimated 60 mph gusts based on numerous branches down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level trough and sufficient moisture combined with local and diurnal effects to generate afternoon shower and thunderstorm, especially across the northwestern quadrant of Puerto Rico and the San Juan metro area. Across the San Juan metro area, a persistent streamer developed and resulted in rainfall accumulations in excess of 3-4 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The central building in the Centro Medico de Puerto Rico complex had the basement flooded.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Residence flooded along Calle Colon. Three people were trapped inside.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent pref-frontal squall line crossed the local forecast area during the late afternoon across SE Georgia and continuing eastward exiting the NE Florida Atlantic coast through midnight.  There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 61 mph was measured at Ben Hill Griffin Station by the WeatherStem gage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation associated with developing low pressure along the Gulf Coast overspread northeast Georgia during the morning. Temperatures were cold enough in most areas for the precipitation to fall, or at least begin as snow. The snow, which was heavy at times quickly accumulated, especially across the mountains. Heavy snowfall totals were realized in many areas by around noon, and by the time the snow tapered off during early/mid afternoon, total accumulations generally ranged from 3 to 5 inches, with locally higher amounts of over 6 inches in the mountains.

A weakening area of precipitation associated with developing low pressure along the Gulf Coast overspread southwest North Carolina during the morning. Temperatures were cold enough in most areas for the precipitation to fall as snow. While heavy snow accumulated in Graham County, total accumulations of 1 to 4 inches were seen for a couple of tier of counties east of there. Due to a warm ground and roads, travel problems were minimal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A trade wind swell, with locally produced wind waves and strong upstream trades, caused surf of 6 to 12 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island.  No significant property damage or injuries were reported. This episode is a continuation from the end of February.

A weakening but still potent upper level low pressure system continued to push east across Arizona during the day on March 13th, and the atmosphere across the central deserts was still very humid and a bit unstable. As the system moved across the greater Phoenix area, scattered afternoon thunderstorms developed over the greater Phoenix area. Some of the thunderstorms generated very heavy rains; a trained spotter near the town of Surprise measured 0.7 inches of rain within a 10 minute period. The heavy rain resulted in episodes of street flooding as well as flash flooding. At about 1700MST flash flooding on Cave Creek near 7th Avenue and Greenway Road. Water 6 inches deep was flowing across 7th Avenue as reported by the public. Heavy rain 3 miles south of Deer Valley caused flash flooding at the Interstate 17 and Greenway underpass to flood. Water 1 to 2 feet deep filled up the underpass resulting in at least one stalled car. A Flash Flood Warning was issued and in effect at the time of the underpass flooding. There were no reports of injuries due to the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy rain, occurred during the afternoon hours across the deserts to the west of Phoenix on March 13th. The heavy rain caused washes, streams and rivers to flow very heavily, posing significant danger to motorists. According to local broadcast media, at 1930MST a motorist became trapped in his vehicle at Baseline Road and 319th Avenue due to the Hassayampa River flowing swiftly across the road. The Hassayampa was swollen and flowing heavily due to the earlier heavy rain in the area. About 20 minutes later, a water rescue was needed for the motorist; the rescue occurred to the west of the town of Buckeye. There were no reports of injuries to either the motorists or the rescuers. There was no flash flood warning in effect at the time of the water rescue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong high pressure over the Desert Southwest led to excessive heat conditions across the Imperial Valley on the 17th.

An upper low, known as a kona low in Hawaii, and concomitant trough developed west of the islands and brought heavy showers, thunderstorms, and flash flooding to the area.  There were no serious injuries.  The costs of any damages were not available.

Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across northeast Georgia from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in flash flooding. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rain began tapering off across northeast Georgia during the afternoon and evening, a stream gauge on the Soque River in Clarkesville indicated continued flooding along the river through the evening. This indicated flooding of Pitts Park along with multiple roads along the river and some of its tributaries.

A powerful Pacific low pressure system spread considerable amounts of deep moisture into much of Imperial County during the day on March 12th and given impressive amounts of lift and instability, this resulted in widespread showers mixed with isolated to scattered thunderstorms. The storms enhanced local rainfall totals, resulting in accumulations that quickly exceeded one inch in some places, resulting in episodes of flooding and flash flooding over the central portions of Imperial County. Flowing water cross over roads to the west and southwest of El Centro leading to road closures. Early evening flooding was observed to the northeast of Brawley, resulting in impacts to local traffic. Flash flood warnings were issued in response to the heavy rain but fortunately there were no injuries resulting from the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and isolated thunderstorms developed during the morning hours across the far southern portions of Imperial County; some of them generated locally heavy rainfall to the southwest of the Imperial Valley. According to local law enforcement, at 0920PST heavy rain in the area south of Seeley led to the closure of State Route 98 at the intersection of Drew Road. There were no flash flood warnings or flood advisories issued for the area and there were no reports of any accidents due to the heavy rain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific storm system brought scattered to numerous showers along with embedded thunderstorms to the deserts of far southeast California on March 20th. Locally heavy rain was observed to have fallen across portions of southeast Imperial County as well as in the vicinity of Yuma. The heavy rain led to some flooding as well as an episode of flash flooding along Ogilby road during the afternoon hours. During the late afternoon, local law enforcement reported flash flooding on portions of Ogilby Road although no accidents occured due to the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific storm system brought widespread rain to portions of far southeast Imperial County on March 10th; rain intensity increased during the early afternoon hours and eventually resulted in flooding to the northwest of Yuma and west of the Colorado River Valley. At 1447PST the California Highway Patrol requested closure of Ogilby Road south of Highway 78 and north of Interstate8 due to rapidly flowing water. There were no reports of accidents due to the flash flooding. A Flash Flood Warning was issued for the area shortly after the road was closed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moisture overspreading a southward-moving cold front resulted in development of precipitation across the North Carolina mountains throughout the daylight hours of the 21st. Temperatures were cold enough in most locations for this precipitation to fall as snow, although rain mixed in at times below about 2500 feet. By the time the snow tapered off during the evening, snowfall totals ranged from trace amounts up to an inch in the lower interior valleys, to 1 to 4 inches above 2500 feet and in the valleys near the Blue Ridge.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across the northern portion of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area during the afternoon hours on March 13th. Some of the stronger storms produced intense rain with peak rain rates well in excess of one inch per hour. The heavy rain resulted in some flash flooding which affected the Interstate 17 corridor to the south of the community of Deer Valley. According to a report from local broadcast media, flash flooding along the Interstate resulted in the flooding of the Greenway Road underpass; one to two feet of water filled up the underpass leading to at least one stalled vehicle. A Flash Flood Warning was issued for the area at 1530MST and it was in effect at the time of the flooding. There were no reports of any injuries fortunately.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms which developed each afternoon along a stationary front in the Plains organized into complexes of storms while diving south of the Red River each night. Instances of wind damage and flooding occurred in a few cases.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A public report indicated Highway 114 just west of the city of Boyd was under water.

A warm, moist airmass was in place across the region ahead of a potent January weather system. Ample wind energy also was present, which not only helped bring damaging winds with severe storms but also allowed for strong gradient winds to occur ahead of an eastward advancing squall line. Severe weather occurred in the early morning hours of January 11th and continued across the ArkLaMiss region before noon, resulting in widespread wind damage as well as some tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and power lines were blown down.

By the time the snow tapered off during the evening, snowfall totals ranged from trace amounts up to an inch in the lower interior valleys, to 1 to 4 inches above 2500 feet and in the valleys near the Blue Ridge.

A moist northwest flow developing in the wake of a strong cold front resulted in snow showers developing near the Tennessee/North Carolina border throughout the 7th. Appreciable snowfall accumulations were primarily confined to Avery and Mitchell Counties, where 2 to 4 inches fell.

A line of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms moved across Upstate South Carolina during the morning in association with a cold front. A few pockets of locally damaging wind gusts developed within the line as it moved east.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: County comms reported trees blown down along Academy Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms moved across Upstate South Carolina during the morning in association with a cold front. A few pockets of locally damaging wind gusts developed within the line as it moved east.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weakening but still potent upper level low pressure system continued to push east across Arizona during the day on March 13th, and the atmosphere across the central deserts was still very humid and a bit unstable. As the system moved across the greater Phoenix area, scattered afternoon thunderstorms developed over the greater Phoenix area. Some of the thunderstorms generated very heavy rains; a trained spotter near the town of Surprise measured 0.7 inches of rain within a 10 minute period. The heavy rain resulted in episodes of street flooding as well as flash flooding. At about 1700MST flash flooding on Cave Creek near 7th Avenue and Greenway Road. Water 6 inches deep was flowing across 7th Avenue as reported by the public. Heavy rain 3 miles south of Deer Valley caused flash flooding at the Interstate 17 and Greenway underpass to flood. Water 1 to 2 feet deep filled up the underpass resulting in at least one stalled car. A Flash Flood Warning was issued and in effect at the time of the underpass flooding. There were no reports of injuries due to the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some with intense rainfall, developed across the northwest portion of the greater Phoenix area during the early afternoon hours on March 13th. The heavy rain affected communities such as Sun City West and Surprise, and resulted in some local street flooding. According to a trained weather spotter located about 1 mile northwest of the town of Surprise, at 1300MST heavy rain resulted in curb to curb flooding in Sun City West along R H Johnson Boulevard. A local storm runoff canal was running with water almost 2 feet deep at the time.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NWS storm survey found the path of a weakening tornado that moved into Lincoln County from Cleveland County in the Hull Rd area before dissipating. Damage was primarily limited to snapped tree limbs and a few downed trees in Lincoln County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across northeast Georgia from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in flash flooding. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A stream gauge on the Soque River in Clarkesville exceeded its established flood stage after 3 to 5 inches of rain fell in the basin in less than 18 hours, with the bulk of that falling in about a 6-hour period during the morning of the 6th. Pitts Park in Clarkesville was flooded, as were multiple roads along the river and some of its tributaries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: From the late evening hours on March 2 into the early morning hours on March 3, supercell thunderstorms developed and spawned tornadoes across southeast Missouri, southern Kentucky, Tennessee, and central Alabama. One of these supercells formed near the Mississippi River in west Tennessee, then tracked eastward across the entire length of the state just north of the Interstate 40 corridor, spawning 10 tornadoes and dropping large hail bigger than the size of baseballs. Seven of these tornadoes touched down across Middle Tennessee, resulting in widespread damage, 307 injuries and 24 fatalities. An additional fatality and 2 more injuries occurred in Benton County in west Tennessee. These tornadoes were the worst seen in Tennessee since the devastating tornadoes of April 27, 2011 across east Tennessee, as well as the Super Tuesday tornadoes of February 5-6, 2008. Total damage estimates from the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency across Middle Tennessee reached $1.6 billion.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A very brief and weak EF-0 tornado touched down just off of Highway 70 and Overstreet Drive southeast of Cookeville in the Goffton area. Damage was mostly to the roof of one house, a metal garage, and an outbuilding. There were also several trees with large branches broken off.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted across the mid-Atlantic early in the morning of August 27, stalling over southern New England. A robust mid-level disturbance along with multiple waves of surface low pressure then tracked along the front during the day. Over southern New England and southern New York, a uniquely favorable environment of high wind shear and high instability contributed to a significant severe weather outbreak. Further south, shear and forcing were a bit weaker. However, thunderstorms eventually progressed southward into the mid-Atlantic, fueled in part by outflow from storms to the north. Some of these storms became severe and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed near Fairmount Ave in Morris Twp. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several reports of downed trees and wires in the Cecilton area. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful Pacific low pressure system spread considerable amounts of deep moisture into much of Imperial County during the day on March 12th and given impressive amounts of lift and instability, this resulted in widespread showers mixed with isolated to scattered thunderstorms. The storms enhanced local rainfall totals, resulting in accumulations that quickly exceeded one inch in some places, resulting in episodes of flooding and flash flooding over the central portions of Imperial County. Flowing water cross over roads to the west and southwest of El Centro leading to road closures. Early evening flooding was observed to the northeast of Brawley, resulting in impacts to local traffic. Flash flood warnings were issued in response to the heavy rain but fortunately there were no injuries resulting from the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some with locally heavy rain, developed and moved slowly across far eastern portions of Imperial County during the afternoon hours on March 12th. The heavy rain led to an episode of flash flooding just west of the lower Colorado River Valley and along State Route 78. According to a reports from the public and Caltrans, at about 1708PST, a vehicle was swept away in a flash flood along State Route 78 about 10 miles south-southwest of Palo Verde. There were multiple people in the vehicle however the California Highway Patrol reported that all of the people were rescued and were in good condition. A Flash Flood Warning was in effect at the time of the rescue. Additionally, at 1926PST local law enforcement reported that multiple vehicles were stuck in or near flood waters at the intersection of State Route 78 and Milpitas Wash Road. This was in the same area as the previous rescue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed through the early morning hours as a low pressure system moved through the Ohio Valley. Some of the storms produced locally heavy rainfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches.

Two children were playing in the water at Ocean Beach and were swept out in a rip current. Their parents went in after them and were also swept out to sea in the same rip current. All four were rescued by a lifeguard and some surfers. Two additional children were also caught in a rip current that same day at Ocean Beach and needed to be rescued.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two children were also caught in a rip current at Ocean Beach and needed to be rescued. Timing is unknown.

Numerous thunderstorms moved across eastern Kentucky this afternoon and evening in association with a mesoscale convective vortex. While many of these storms were below severe limits, a few were able to pulse strong enough to produce damaging winds across portions of southeast Kentucky up through the Interstate 75 corridor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dispatch reported downed trees from near Strunk to Pine Knot.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rain tapered off across the Catawba River basin throughout the afternoon of the 6th, floodwaters continued to rise along the South Fork Catawba, as runoff from 4 to 6 inches of rain continued to work its way through the watershed. Major flood stage was reached by late evening of the 6th, and the worst flooding since 2013 was observed in the Cramerton and McAdenville areas. Flooding of multiple structures occurred, particularly along Riverside Dr and 8th Ave in Cramerton. Otherwise, numerous roads were inundated, including some due to backwater effects along tributaries of the South Fork Catawba.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level trough located north of the an area and abundant moisture combined with local and diurnal effects to generate afternoon showers and thunderstorms across the northwestern quadrant of Puerto Rico. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent pref-frontal squall line crossed the local forecast area during the late afternoon across SE Georgia and continuing eastward exiting the NE Florida Atlantic coast through midnight.  There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down in Hastings. Spotter estimated wind gusts to 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong area of high pressure parked over the Southwest United States led to continued excessive heat conditions across the region from the end of July into the beginning of August. Temperatures each day climbed near or above 110 degrees with a daily record high of 114 degrees being set in Phoenix on the 3rd. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 40 heat-associated fatalities occurred with this event for the beginning of August.

A warm front lifted across the mid-Atlantic early in the morning of August 27, stalling over southern New England. A robust mid-level disturbance along with multiple waves of surface low pressure then tracked along the front during the day. Over southern New England and southern New York, a uniquely favorable environment of high wind shear and high instability contributed to a significant severe weather outbreak. Further south, shear and forcing were a bit weaker. However, thunderstorms eventually progressed southward into the mid-Atlantic, fueled in part by outflow from storms to the north. Some of these storms became severe and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several reports of downed trees and power lines in the vicinity of Tumble Creek Rd. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse, slow moving frontal boundary was present over the mid-Atlantic on August 3 as an upper level trough also approached from the west. Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaias was steadily approaching from the south, with tropical moisture beginning to overspread the region. The result was a warm and humid day on August 3. This created an unstable environment, and forcing from the frontal boundary as well as the approaching trough helped to trigger afternoon thunderstorm development. Shear also increased as mid level winds increased ahead of the trough and Isaias. This led to a considerable severe weather event in advance of Isaias, with multiple clusters of thunderstorms producing scattered and in some cases significant wind damage over New Jersey.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed on Cooper Ln near Tiger Brook Park in Chester. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed through the early morning hours as a low pressure system moved through the Ohio Valley. Some of the storms produced locally heavy rainfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A bridge collapsed on Sanes Creek Road near Tee Hill Road due to flash flooding on Sanes Creek. Two vehicles were swept into the water, leading to six fatalities. M48VE, M47VE, F35VE, M13VE, F7VE, F4VE.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous thunderstorms moved across eastern Kentucky this afternoon and evening in association with a mesoscale convective vortex. While many of these storms were below severe limits, a few were able to pulse strong enough to produce damaging winds across portions of southeast Kentucky up through the Interstate 75 corridor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A citizen observed trees downed northwest of Annville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: After a week of heavy, wind blown snow across the Central Colorado Rockies where up to four feet of snow had fallen, back country recreationists unintentionally triggered a hard slab avalanche while riding motorized snow-bikes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A hard slab avalanche was unintentionally triggered by 3 motorized snow-bikers following a week of heavy, wind blown snow in the South Fork of Dickson Creek, east of Red and White Mountain. The avalanche was 3 to 4 feet in depth, 600 feet wide and debris ran for about 300 vertical feet. The avalanche was described a medium-sized and produced enough force to injure, bury, or kill a person. All 3 of the snow-bikers were trapped or partially buried. Only 1 survived.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Northeast winds of 20 to 30 mph over western Lake Erie and high water levels and waves caused lakeshore flooding and erosion  along the Monroe Shoreline. The water level at Toledo peaked at 72 inches near midnight on February 5th.
A potent upper level disturbance produced a long duration snow event late February 25th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals ranged between 4 and 8 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Periods of light to occasionally moderate snow and below freezing temperatures created difficult travel conditions late February 25th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals across the county generally ranged between 6 and 8 inches. Untreated and lesser traveled roads became snow covered and slick in spots, especially during the overnight and morning hours. Numerous school cancellations and slide-offs were reported across the region.

A warm front lifted through the mid-Atlantic on the morning of August 23, bringing some showers with it. After a midday lull in precipitation, a lee side surface trough helped to initiate some thunderstorms in a moist and moderately unstable environment. The relatively weak forcing and limited shear prevented much storm organization, but a few storms did become strong to severe with a few instances of damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were downed near Maryland Ave. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed across portions of southern Gila County during the afternoon hours on August 1st. One of the stronger storms produced large hail with diameters of about one inch. The large hailstones fell in the town of Peridot, and in one instance window damage was reported due to the hail. A Severe Thunderstorm Warning was issued shortly after the large hail reports. No injuries were reported due to the large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with large hail developed near the town of Peridot in southern Gila County during the afternoon hours on August 1st. At 1633MST, a teacher at a local school in Peridot reported quarter sized hail. Some of the largest stones had a diameter of one inch and were large enough to break a window at one of the residences on campus. At about the same time, penny to nickle sized hailstones were reported by the public in town, at the Bashas store along US Highway 70. No damage or injuries were reported from those hailstones.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed to the southeast of Phoenix and over portions of northern Pinal County during the evening hours on August 11th. Some of the stronger storms generated gusty outflow winds that reached to at least 40 mph; the winds were sufficient to cause areas of blowing dust that lowered visibility to one quarter mile or below. From about 1900MST to 1930MST, multiple spotter and public reports were taken between Casa Grande and the Ak Chin Indian Reservation indicating dense blowing dust lowering visibility to one quarter mile or below. There were no dust storm warnings issued and no accidents or injuries resulted from the severely restricted visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed to the southeast of Phoenix during the evening hours on August 11th and some of the stronger storms generated gusty outflow winds which reached to about 40 mph. The winds were strong enough to generate areas of dense blowing dust that impacted portions of northwest Pinal County, from Casa Grande northwest to the Ak Chin Indian Reservation. At 1926MST, a member of the public located about 1 mile southeast of the town of Maricopa reported less than one quarter of a mile visibility in a dust storm. At about the same time, a trained weather spotter 4 miles north of Casa Grande reported visibility down to one eighth of a mile in a dust storm. A bit earlier at about 1910MST, the official AWOS weather station at the Ak Chin Airport measured one quarter of a mile visibility in blowing dust with wind gusts to 38 mph. A Dust Storm Warning was not issued; fortunately there were no reports of accidents or injury due to the dust storm and the sharply restricted visibilities.

There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A private weather station near Matanzas Inlet measured a gust to 50 mph.

A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees and power lines were downed in the area. Time estimated from radar.

A mid-level impulse moved over the mid-Atlantic on August 24. A moist and moderate to strongly unstable environment was present as this disturbance moved through, which led to the development of scattered showers and thunderstorms. Weak shear prevented storms from becoming well organized, but the instability allowed a couple of storms to become strong to severe and produce a few instances of damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed near Frable Dr south of Gilbert. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Outflow winds downed trees and destroyed a transformer. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front along with a mid-level shortwave trough approached the mid-Atlantic on August 25. Ahead of the disturbances, wind shear increased significantly and surface temperatures warmed, increasing instability. While some ingredients were in place for a major severe weather event, an offset in timing between the shortwave and the front, combined with greater than expected mid-level dry air, caused storms to generally struggle to develop over the mid-Atlantic. Greater storm coverage was found in more favorable environments over both New England and the Ohio Valley. However, the environment over the mid-Atlantic was still highly favorable for damaging winds, so the few storms that did develop produced some instances of wind damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation began to overspread eastern Kentucky late on February 28, extending into the morning hours of the 29th. Temperatures above freezing led to this beginning as rain, before transitioning to snow during the late evening and overnight. Most locations across eastern Kentucky saw measurable snow, but Harlan and Letcher Counties were the only ones to see much in the way of impacts as roads became at least partially snow covered in the higher elevations. Snowfall amounts of 3-4 inches were reported over the span of the event across portions of the two counties.

A well defined cold front that stretched from Chicago to the Gulf Coast, moved west to east through the Ohio Valley. This produced several thunderstorms that caused widespread damage throughout the Bluegrass region of Kentucky. The Kentucky Mesonet  recorded a 77 mph wind gust within one of these storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees and power lines were reported down along Grasmere Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper low across the Gulf of Maine continually rotated showers and thunderstorms across VT with a focused path across portions of the western slopes of VT's Green Mountains. During the late afternoon of June 30th, thunderstorms back-built in the Hinesburg, Monkton, Starksboro area quickly producing 4+ inches of rainfall within two hours. This led to some localized flash flooding, especially gravel roads in the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooded roads and partial gravel road washouts along State Prison Road in Starksboro and Monkton as well as water lapping several roads in the neighboring vicinity.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper low along with a second shortwave trough moved through the region the first weekend of June. A strong onshore pressure gradient brought gusty winds to much of the area. Observations showed gusts of 40 to 60 mph throughout the Bay Area and Central Coast. These winds fueled multiple grass and vegetation fires throughout the area, some of which prompted evacuations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind-driven grass fire reported in the San Francisco neighborhood of Potrero Hill. Evacuations were issued, the fire was contained with no structures damaged https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2020/06/05/grass-fire-in-san-franciscos-potrero-hill-forces-evacuations/.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front pushed across the region and produced moderate snow over the northern and portions of the central Colorado mountains as well as the Central Colorado River Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 3 to 5 inches of snow fell across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous disturbances embedded in a decaying atmospheric river produced moderate to heavy snow over the northwest and west-central Colorado mountains. Portions of the Park Range received over 3 feet of snow. Sustained wind speeds exceeded 20 MPH at times with gusts of up to 48 MPH recorded.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 18 to 30 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts close to 40 inches estimated at the Tower SNOTEL site. Sustained wind speeds exceeded 20 MPH at times. Travel was severely impacted along Colorado Highway 40 with Rabbit Ears Pass being closed for a period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep tropical moisture was in place (PWAT 2.5) with the area on the east side of TS |Cristobal as the storm approached the LA Gulf Coast. Waves of moderate to heavy rainfall with isolated embedded thunderstorms pivoted northward across the local forecast area into the evening with a more solid band of moderate to heavy rainfall developing across north Florida as low level convergence increased between a lifting frontal zones across south-central  FL and a persistent low level ridge axis holding firm just north of the Altamaha River basin. This ridge will limit the northward extend/expansion of the convective band into Sun, and generally focused a W-E oriented swath of heavy rainfall generally near and south of the I-10 corridor overnight into Sunday morning on 6/7.  The ridge strengthened north of the Altamaha Region Sun afternoon 6/7, which shunt the corridor of heavy rain SSW toward the I-75 corridor of NE FL with drier mid level air (700-500 mb) decreasing rain chances across SE GA and eastern NE FL into Sun evening. In addition to heavy rainfall potential, there was a low tornado threat for NE FL into the evening of 6/6 with elevated 0-1 km shear values 20-25 kts with low level ESE winds under increasing  SSW winds out of the GOMEX, with speeds increasing to 35-45 kts at 850 mb through 06z Sun 6/7.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and power lines were damaged by thunderstorm wind gusts from Belleview to Summerfield along SE 95th Court, NW 20th Ave, 92th Loop and SE 126th Place.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A sharp cold front lied across far southern Minnesota during the afternoon of Tuesday, June 2nd. Temperatures ahead of this front rose into the mid to upper 90s with 70s and 80s behind it. In addition, dew points dropped significantly behind the front across central Minnesota. ||During the late morning, and early afternoon, elevated convection developed across central Minnesota and moved eastward but continued to develop on the southwest flank. Numerous hail stones were reported, but most were sub-severe. A few stronger updrafts contributed to a few hail stones as large as golf ball size near Alexandria. As the storms moved farther to the southeast, reports of large hail was observed near Elk River. ||By the mid-late afternoon, severe thunderstorms developed along a cold front across far southern Minnesota. Initially, most of the reports were very large hail, south of the Minnesota River, from around Lake Crystal, Garden City, Vernon Center and Good Thunder. There was a measured hail stone of 2.5 inches in diameter near Garden City. There was another measured report of 2.0 inches near Waldorf.  ||All of the significant wind damage reports were from the areas around New Richland, Waldorf, Hollandale, Myrtle, Albert Lea, Lewisville, and other areas of south central Minnesota due to severe thunderstorm outflow winds.  The storms were |highly visible from miles away and dozens of people took pictures and video.

A strong cold front combined with a tight pressure gradient, instability aloft, and favorable upper level dynamics moved across western Colorado. This system produced moderate snow over the northern and central mountains as well as gusty winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 6 to 12 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts up to 16.5 inches estimated at the Tower SNOTEL site. Sustained wind speeds exceeded 20 to 30 MPH for several hours which led to reduced visibility in blowing snow. This resulted in severe travel impacts along Colorado Highway 40 with Rabbit Ears Pass being closed for at least an hour.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of a swell from the southern hemisphere and a trade wind swell generated surf of 6 to 12 feet along the east- and south-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island; and along the south-facing shores of Niihau, Lanai, and Kahoolawe.  No serious injuries or property damage were reported.

An upper low, known as a kona low in Hawaii, and concomitant trough developed west of the islands and brought heavy showers, thunderstorms, and flash flooding to the area.  There were no serious injuries.  The costs of any damages were not available.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Kamehameha Highway was closed at the Waikane Stream near Waikane in windward Oahu because of flooding waters.  A vehicle became stuck in the area, and a home on Nanamoa Street also was flooded due to a clogged drain.  Costs of any damages were not available.|There were no serious injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain to Berks County during the early hours of August 2.  Rainfall totals as high as 4 to 6 inches fell in the county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread flooding occurred in Maidencreek Township.  Main Street in Blandon was closed at the railroad tracks.  US Route 222 was under water at Dries Road.  Willow Creek was out of its banks at a number of locations in the township.  A tributary of Willow Creek was also out of its banks and caused flooding on Cornerstone Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain to Berks County during the early hours of August 2.  Rainfall totals as high as 4 to 6 inches fell in the county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread flooding occurred in Muhlenberg Township and in Laureldale.  There were a number of water rescues in the area.  The intersection of Darby Avenue and 6th Avenue was under water.  PA Route 12 was closed between PA Route 61 and the 5th Street Highway.  Flooding occurred around the intersection of Hain Avenue and Laurel Run Avenue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse, slow moving frontal boundary was present over the mid-Atlantic on August 3 as an upper level trough also approached from the west. Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaias was steadily approaching from the south, with tropical moisture beginning to overspread the region. The result was a warm and humid day on August 3. This created an unstable environment, and forcing from the frontal boundary as well as the approaching trough helped to trigger afternoon thunderstorm development. Shear also increased as mid level winds increased ahead of the trough and Isaias. This led to a considerable severe weather event in advance of Isaias, with multiple clusters of thunderstorms producing scattered and in some cases significant wind damage over New Jersey.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down in Bedminster. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front along with a mid-level shortwave trough approached the mid-Atlantic on August 25. Ahead of the disturbances, wind shear increased significantly and surface temperatures warmed, increasing instability. While some ingredients were in place for a major severe weather event, an offset in timing between the shortwave and the front, combined with greater than expected mid-level dry air, caused storms to generally struggle to develop over the mid-Atlantic. Greater storm coverage was found in more favorable environments over both New England and the Ohio Valley. However, the environment over the mid-Atlantic was still highly favorable for damaging winds, so the few storms that did develop produced some instances of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree and wires were downed at North East Rd and Nazarene Camp Rd. Time estimated from radar.

At 905 am, the Duval County EM reported water up to 3 feet deep halfway up the stop sign at the intersection of McCoy Creek Blvd and King Street. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions developed rapidly across New Hampshire starting in the middle of May. The period May 16 to June 25 was exceedingly dry. There was some relief in late June and July, especially in the White Mountains and parts of southwest New Hampshire due to thunderstorm activity. By the middle of August, dry conditions set in again with September being exceedingly dry with some locations reporting their driest September on record. The National Centers for Environmental Information reported that September was the 7th driest on record for New Hampshire. D2 severe drought was confined to coastal New Hampshire, the Merrimack River Valley and the Lakes Region during the beginning of the month. The D2 severe drought rapidly expanded through the entire state by the end of September. An area of D3 extreme drought area developing towards the end of September in Southeast New Hampshire with Strafford County being the hardest hit, along with regions of surrounding counties.  The drought peaked in intensity during the first week of October before beneficial widespread rains impacted the state towards the middle of October.  Concord received a monthly rainfall total of 5.11, Manchester received 4.01, Whitfield received 5.48, and Durham received 4.59.  Towards the middle of the month most of Coos County was reduced from D2 Severe Drought to D1 Moderate Drought.  Drought classification continued to improve by the third week in October due to the heavy rains. Grafton, Sullivan, and Cheshire Counties were reduced from D2 Severe Drought to D1 Moderate Drought. The northern and western sections of Carroll, Belknap, Merrimack and Hillsborough Counties also showed a drought classification improvement by the end of the month. Severe and Extreme drought remained across southeast New Hampshire through the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The drought peaked in intensity during the first week of October before beneficial widespread rains impacted the state towards the middle of October. Concord received a monthly rainfall total of 5.11, Manchester received 4.01, Whitefield received 5.48, and Durham received 4.59. Even with the October rainfall, deficits since Jan 1st remained at -9.77 at Concord, -10.66 at Whitefield and -12.42 at Manchester. Drought monitor classifications in October had a positive trend or maintained with no worsening of drought conditions in part of the state.  During the first week of October 95% of the state was in D2 Severe drought and 22% of the state was in D3 Extreme drought.  By the end of the month the areal extent of D2 Severe drought had decreased to 33% of the state and D3 Extreme drought decreased to 17% of the state.  Overall, the greatest improvements were across Northern and Western New Hampshire, where D1 Moderate drought remained.  Severe and Extreme drought remained centered across southeast New Hampshire by the end of the month.  Hydrologic conditions continued to worsen in the first week of October on non-regulated rivers with 81% of USGS river gaging stations below normal and 9% of sites at record lows for the beginning of October.  Hydrologic conditions began to improve by mid-month due to the heavy rainfall with most river basins near the normal range by the end of October. Reservoir levels continued to trend below normal on the upper Connecticut River along with Lake Winnipesaukee which remained half a foot below normal by the end of the month. Overall lake levels were on par with the 2016 drought. In New Hampshire of the monitoring wells maintained by the USGS and the state of New Hampshire, the majority were below average with record low levels across southeast New Hampshire for the date. Numerous water bans and restrictions remained in effect during the month of October with virtually all towns in Southern and Central New Hampshire having issued a water ban impacting 400,000 residents.  An estimated 1000 private residents had dry wells with state agencies reporting over 100 applicants fore well assistance. Corn, potatoes, barley fruit crops and forage crops were the most affected. Farmers were concerned about having enough forage for their livestock to get through the winter. Dairy industry was especially impacted due to low grass yields.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent upper level disturbance produced a long duration snow event late February 25th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals ranged between 3 and 7 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Periods of light to occasionally moderate snow and below freezing temperatures created difficult travel conditions February 26th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals across the county generally ranged between 3 and 5 inches. Untreated and lesser traveled roads became snow covered and slick in spots, especially during the overnight and morning hours. Numerous school cancellations and slide-offs were reported across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent pref-frontal squall line crossed the local forecast area during the late afternoon across SE Georgia and continuing eastward exiting the NE Florida Atlantic coast through midnight.  There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread trees and power lines were blown down across the county. No major structural damage was reported to homes. The time of damage was based on radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong area of high pressure parked over the Southwest United States led to continued excessive heat conditions across the region from the end of July into the beginning of August. Temperatures each day climbed near or above 110 degrees with a daily record high of 114 degrees being set in Phoenix on the 3rd. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 40 heat-associated fatalities occurred with this event for the beginning of August.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six heat-associated fatalities were reported by the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, with their details, such as age, gender, circumstances and location unavailable.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Monsoon thunderstorms developed across portions of the south central Arizona deserts during the evening hours on August 16th. Some of the stronger storms generated very strong and gusty outflow winds that approached 80 mph in strength at times. At about 2050MST a traveler on Interstate 8 reported significant roof, tree and car damage from a collapsing thunderstorm near the Sentinel rest area. Earlier, at about 1745MST a member of the public located 7 miles northeast of Wittmann reported about 20 trees blown down on a local golf course. The larger trees had diameters of about 12 inches, and the damage was consistent with wind gusts of at least 60 mph. There were no reports of injuries due to the strong and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with strong, damaging outflow winds developed near the town of Wittmann during late afternoon hours on August 16th. At about 1744MST, a member of the public located 7 miles northeast of Wittmann reported that strong winds blew down about 20 trees at a local golf course. The diameter of the largest trees was about 12 inches. Peak wind gusts were estimated by radar to be at least 60 mph in strength. The gusty winds also did additional damage such as to fencing, as reported by the course manager. There were no reports of injury due to the strong winds.

According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 40 heat-associated fatalities occurred with this event for the beginning of August.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Twenty-six heat-associated fatalities were reported by the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, with their details, such as age, gender, circumstances and location unavailable.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported winds in excess of 60 mph at Hacks Point on MD-213. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weakening but still potent upper level low pressure system continued to push east across Arizona during the day on March 13th, and the atmosphere across the central deserts was still very humid and a bit unstable. As the system moved across the greater Phoenix area, scattered afternoon thunderstorms developed over the greater Phoenix area. Some of the thunderstorms generated very heavy rains; a trained spotter near the town of Surprise measured 0.7 inches of rain within a 10 minute period. The heavy rain resulted in episodes of street flooding as well as flash flooding. At about 1700MST flash flooding on Cave Creek near 7th Avenue and Greenway Road. Water 6 inches deep was flowing across 7th Avenue as reported by the public. Heavy rain 3 miles south of Deer Valley caused flash flooding at the Interstate 17 and Greenway underpass to flood. Water 1 to 2 feet deep filled up the underpass resulting in at least one stalled car. A Flash Flood Warning was issued and in effect at the time of the underpass flooding. There were no reports of injuries due to the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An exiting but still potent upper level disturbance acted upon a still wet and unstable air mass to produce scattered afternoon thunderstorms across portions of the greater Phoenix metropolitan area on March 13th. Some of the stronger storms generated locally heavy rain with peak rain rates well in excess of one inch per hour. Portions of the heavy rain fell in the community of Buckeye resulting in an episode of flash flooding. According to a trained weather spotter located about 3 miles north of the town of Buckeye, at 1605MST flash flooding resulted in flowing water 6 inches deep covering a 20 foot wide swath across Miller Road, just south of lower Buckeye Road. Despite the quickly flowing water there were no reports of any accidents due to the flash flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed through the early morning hours as a low pressure system moved through the Ohio Valley. Some of the storms produced locally heavy rainfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed along Wales Road. Some business signs and a cupola on a bank building were also damaged near the intersection of I-71 and Fields Ertel Road. A semi-trailer was partially blown over on I-71 near mile marker 19.

There was very strong speed shear over the local area with strong 0-6km shear around 55 knots, 0-1km helicity over 300 m2/s2, and sufficient CAPE for severe weather. The limiting factor was fairly weak mid-level lapse rates. Widespread wind damage occurred with this line with gusts of 40-50 mph and severe strength bowing segments producing wind damage and gusts of 60-76 mph. A isolated tornado briefly touched down in Waycross.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter estimated wind gusts of 60-65 mph in Yulee.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong high pressure over the region allowed for temperatures to climb above 110 degrees on the 9th and 10th, promoting excessive heat conditions. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 5 heat-associated fatalities occurred during this event.

Thunderstorms developed over the deserts to the west of Phoenix during the afternoon hours on July 23rd and some of the stronger storms generated locally heavy rainfall. The heavy rain was sufficient to lead to an episode of flash flooding to the southwest of Phoenix, between Gila Bend and Buckeye, just to the west of Highway 85. The flash flooding resulted in the closure of old Highway 80 about 15 miles southwest of Buckeye. The highway was closed by Rainbow Wash and the flooding was captured on video by a trained spotter. There were no reports of accidents or injury due to the flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with heavy rain developed to the southwest of Phoenix during the afternoon hours on July 23rd, resulting in an episode of flash flooding approximately 15 miles to the southwest of the town of Buckeye. Flash flooding resulted in the closure of old US 80 at Rainbow Wash at about 1515MST. The wash quickly rose over 3.5 feet. The timing of the flooding was based on stream gage data from the Maricopa County Flood Control network. Flash flooding was observed on video by a trained weather spotter; he could see the flood waters moving through the wash and approaching highway 80. There were no reports of accidents or injury due to the flash flooding.

A diffuse, slow moving frontal boundary was present over the mid-Atlantic on August 3 as an upper level trough also approached from the west. Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaias was steadily approaching from the south, with tropical moisture beginning to overspread the region. The result was a warm and humid day on August 3. This created an unstable environment, and forcing from the frontal boundary as well as the approaching trough helped to trigger afternoon thunderstorm development. Shear also increased as mid level winds increased ahead of the trough and Isaias. This led to a considerable severe weather event in advance of Isaias, with multiple clusters of thunderstorms producing scattered and in some cases significant wind damage over New Jersey.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wires were reported down in the area. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted across the mid-Atlantic early in the morning of August 27, stalling over southern New England. A robust mid-level disturbance along with multiple waves of surface low pressure then tracked along the front during the day. Over southern New England and southern New York, a uniquely favorable environment of high wind shear and high instability contributed to a significant severe weather outbreak. Further south, shear and forcing were a bit weaker. However, thunderstorms eventually progressed southward into the mid-Atlantic, fueled in part by outflow from storms to the north. Some of these storms became severe and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed into a house on Jeffrey Rd. Time based on a reported wind gust at nearby Reading Regional Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep tropical moisture was in place (PWAT 2.5) with the area on the east side of TS |Cristobal as the storm approached the LA Gulf Coast. Waves of moderate to heavy rainfall with isolated embedded thunderstorms pivoted northward across the local forecast area into the evening with a more solid band of moderate to heavy rainfall developing across north Florida as low level convergence increased between a lifting frontal zones across south-central  FL and a persistent low level ridge axis holding firm just north of the Altamaha River basin. This ridge will limit the northward extend/expansion of the convective band into Sun, and generally focused a W-E oriented swath of heavy rainfall generally near and south of the I-10 corridor overnight into Sunday morning on 6/7.  The ridge strengthened north of the Altamaha Region Sun afternoon 6/7, which shunt the corridor of heavy rain SSW toward the I-75 corridor of NE FL with drier mid level air (700-500 mb) decreasing rain chances across SE GA and eastern NE FL into Sun evening. In addition to heavy rainfall potential, there was a low tornado threat for NE FL into the evening of 6/6 with elevated 0-1 km shear values 20-25 kts with low level ESE winds under increasing  SSW winds out of the GOMEX, with speeds increasing to 35-45 kts at 850 mb through 06z Sun 6/7.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 330 pm a tornado touched down near Bradshaw Road where it damaged trees. The tornado tracked north-northeast and continued to snap trees as it tracked across SW Bellmont Drive and damage a small barn as it nearly paralleled State Road 47. The tornado path then tracked NNE along SW State Road 47 where it damaged large oak trees and power lines. The tornado peaked in intensity in this area with max winds around 85 mph. The tornado lifted just east of the State Road 47 along SW Wester Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were downed in the vicinity of Ruppert School Rd in Pike Twp. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation began to overspread eastern Kentucky late on February 28, extending into the morning hours of the 29th. Temperatures above freezing led to this beginning as rain, before transitioning to snow during the late evening and overnight. Most locations across eastern Kentucky saw measurable snow, but Harlan and Letcher Counties were the only ones to see much in the way of impacts as roads became at least partially snow covered in the higher elevations. Snowfall amounts of 3-4 inches were reported over the span of the event across portions of the two counties.
A cold front pushed across the region and produced moderate snow over the northern and portions of the central Colorado mountains as well as the Central Colorado River Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area with 11 inches estimated at the Rabbit Ears Pass SNOTEL site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The 2nd longest heatwave in modern history (1900-onward) occurred across portions of NY and VT from June 18th through June 23rd. Temperatures exceeded 90 degrees for up to 6 consecutive days in portions of the St. Lawrence and Champlain Valleys. Daily High temperature records were set at Massena on June 22nd and June 23rd with high temperatures of 93 and 92 degrees respectively.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High temperatures in the upper 80s to lower 90s for many parts of the St. Lawrence Valley for six days with increasing humidity on the tail end of this stretch, bringing heat indices into the mid 90s.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees and power lines downed by thunderstorm winds on the north and east sides of Gouverneur.
