A warm, moist airmass was in place across the region ahead of a potent January weather system. Ample wind energy also was present, which not only helped bring damaging winds with severe storms but also allowed for strong gradient winds to occur ahead of an eastward advancing squall line. Severe weather occurred in the early morning hours of January 11th and continued across the ArkLaMiss region before noon, resulting in widespread wind damage as well as some tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Streets were flooded in West Point.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep tropical moisture was in place (PWAT 2.5) with the area on the east side of TS |Cristobal as the storm approached the LA Gulf Coast. Waves of moderate to heavy rainfall with isolated embedded thunderstorms pivoted northward across the local forecast area into the evening with a more solid band of moderate to heavy rainfall developing across north Florida as low level convergence increased between a lifting frontal zones across south-central  FL and a persistent low level ridge axis holding firm just north of the Altamaha River basin. This ridge will limit the northward extend/expansion of the convective band into Sun, and generally focused a W-E oriented swath of heavy rainfall generally near and south of the I-10 corridor overnight into Sunday morning on 6/7.  The ridge strengthened north of the Altamaha Region Sun afternoon 6/7, which shunt the corridor of heavy rain SSW toward the I-75 corridor of NE FL with drier mid level air (700-500 mb) decreasing rain chances across SE GA and eastern NE FL into Sun evening. In addition to heavy rainfall potential, there was a low tornado threat for NE FL into the evening of 6/6 with elevated 0-1 km shear values 20-25 kts with low level ESE winds under increasing  SSW winds out of the GOMEX, with speeds increasing to 35-45 kts at 850 mb through 06z Sun 6/7.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total daily rainfall at a mesonet site measured 4.59 inches along SW 108th Lane in Belleview. Other observations around this location measured 3.5 to 4.5 inches of rainfall in the past 2 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked from southwest Iowa to north central Iowa Saturday afternoon. Storms developed, moved across a warm front, and four tornadoes touched down over eastern Iowa and northwest Illinois.  A few other storms brought small hail and damaging wind to portions of the region Saturday night.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado touched down north of Jesup, Iowa about 615 PM CDT, March 28th. The tornado moved northeast and caused damage to outbuildings and a barn, and uprooted trees at a farmstead. The tornado was on the ground for about 10 minutes, and traveled a little more than 7 miles. The tornado was rated EF-1, with maximum winds around 90 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse, slow moving frontal boundary was present over the mid-Atlantic on August 3 as an upper level trough also approached from the west. Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaias was steadily approaching from the south, with tropical moisture beginning to overspread the region. The result was a warm and humid day on August 3. This created an unstable environment, and forcing from the frontal boundary as well as the approaching trough helped to trigger afternoon thunderstorm development. Shear also increased as mid level winds increased ahead of the trough and Isaias. This led to a considerable severe weather event in advance of Isaias, with multiple clusters of thunderstorms producing scattered and in some cases significant wind damage over New Jersey.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At least one tree was downed in Monroe. Time estimated from radar.

Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across northeast Georgia from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in flash flooding. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding developed along the Beaverdam Creek basin in northern Elbert County after 3 to 5 inches of rain fell in about 24 hours, with much of that falling during the morning and afternoon of the 6th. Multiple roads were flooded along the stream from Bowman through Dewy Rose into areas just north of Elberton.

CZ_NAME: GORE AND ELK MOUNTAINS/CENTRAL MOUNTAIN VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front combined with a tight pressure gradient, instability aloft, and favorable upper level dynamics moved across western Colorado. This system produced moderate snow over the northern and central mountains as well as gusty winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area. Wind gusted from 55 to 65 MPH for several hours which led to reduced visibility in blowing snow. This resulted in severe travel impacts along Interstate 70 with Vail Pass being closed for a couple of hours due to whiteout conditions as a snow squall moved overhead. The Aspen Airport recorded visibility of 1/4 mile and a peak wind gust of 55 MPH with this squall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front combined with a tight pressure gradient, instability aloft, and favorable upper level dynamics moved across western Colorado. This system produced moderate snow over the northern and central mountains as well as gusty winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area. Winds gusted up to 62 MPH at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent upper level disturbance produced a long duration snow event late February 25th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals ranged between 4 and 8 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Periods of light to occasionally moderate snow and below freezing temperatures created difficult travel conditions late February 25th through early February 27th. Snowfall totals across the county generally ranged between 5 and 7 inches. Untreated and lesser traveled roads became snow covered and slick in spots, especially during the overnight and morning hours. Numerous school cancellations and slide-offs were reported across the region.

Observations showed gusts of 40 to 60 mph throughout the Bay Area and Central Coast. These winds fueled multiple grass and vegetation fires throughout the area, some of which prompted evacuations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Big Rock RAWS station reported wind gusts between 40 and 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lingering stationary boundary along the I-70 corridor was the focus for renewed thunderstorm activity during the late evening hours of March 27th. Another round of severe storms with large hail occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wide swath of large hail fell between St. Martins and Jefferson City. The largest hail stones were 3 inches in diameter.  There were numerous reports of dents on vehicles and car windows broken out.  At least 800 hundred cars sustained damage at car dealerships in the Jefferson City area. The largest hail stones were reported in St. Martins, Elston, and Jefferson City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lingering stationary boundary along the I-70 corridor was the focus for renewed thunderstorm activity during the late evening hours of March 27th. Another round of severe storms with large hail occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wide swath of large hail fell across southern portions of Callaway County. Hail up to the size of baseballs was reported in Holts Summit and the Lake Mykee areas. There were reports of damage to several vehicles including broken windshields.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lingering stationary boundary along the I-70 corridor was the focus for renewed thunderstorm activity during the late evening hours of March 27th. Another round of severe storms with large hail occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large hail up to baseball size was reported in far northern portions of Osage County in the Chamois area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across northeast Georgia from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in flash flooding. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rain tapered off across Elbert County during the evening, stream levels on Beaverdam Creek continued to rise steadily throughout the morning of the 7th, and a stream gauge on the creek north of Elberton reflected the most significant flooding in at least 32 years. Major flooding occurred along the stream, with multiple roads washed out and water inundating at least one business along Brewers Bridge Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: County comms and stream gauges reported flash flooding developed across Henderson County after 4 to 5 inches of rain fell across the area in about 24 hours, with much of that falling during the morning and afternoon of the 7th. Multiple roads were inundated and closed throughout the county due to a combination of poor drainage and small stream flooding. This included Mud Creek near downtown Hendersonville, which flooded areas near S Church St and S Main St.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep tropical moisture was in place (PWAT 2.5) with the area on the east side of TS |Cristobal as the storm approached the LA Gulf Coast. Waves of moderate to heavy rainfall with isolated embedded thunderstorms pivoted northward across the local forecast area into the evening with a more solid band of moderate to heavy rainfall developing across north Florida as low level convergence increased between a lifting frontal zones across south-central  FL and a persistent low level ridge axis holding firm just north of the Altamaha River basin. This ridge will limit the northward extend/expansion of the convective band into Sun, and generally focused a W-E oriented swath of heavy rainfall generally near and south of the I-10 corridor overnight into Sunday morning on 6/7.  The ridge strengthened north of the Altamaha Region Sun afternoon 6/7, which shunt the corridor of heavy rain SSW toward the I-75 corridor of NE FL with drier mid level air (700-500 mb) decreasing rain chances across SE GA and eastern NE FL into Sun evening. In addition to heavy rainfall potential, there was a low tornado threat for NE FL into the evening of 6/6 with elevated 0-1 km shear values 20-25 kts with low level ESE winds under increasing  SSW winds out of the GOMEX, with speeds increasing to 35-45 kts at 850 mb through 06z Sun 6/7.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer measured 7.44 inches of rainfall since midnight.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were downed in the vicinity of Old Gibraltar Rd. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse, slow moving frontal boundary was present over the mid-Atlantic on August 3 as an upper level trough also approached from the west. Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaias was steadily approaching from the south, with tropical moisture beginning to overspread the region. The result was a warm and humid day on August 3. This created an unstable environment, and forcing from the frontal boundary as well as the approaching trough helped to trigger afternoon thunderstorm development. Shear also increased as mid level winds increased ahead of the trough and Isaias. This led to a considerable severe weather event in advance of Isaias, with multiple clusters of thunderstorms producing scattered and in some cases significant wind damage over New Jersey.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An NWS employee estimated 60 mph wind gusts along with minor tree damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front along with a mid-level shortwave trough approached the mid-Atlantic on August 25. Ahead of the disturbances, wind shear increased significantly and surface temperatures warmed, increasing instability. While some ingredients were in place for a major severe weather event, an offset in timing between the shortwave and the front, combined with greater than expected mid-level dry air, caused storms to generally struggle to develop over the mid-Atlantic. Greater storm coverage was found in more favorable environments over both New England and the Ohio Valley. However, the environment over the mid-Atlantic was still highly favorable for damaging winds, so the few storms that did develop produced some instances of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported blown down in Denton. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted across the mid-Atlantic early in the morning of August 27, stalling over southern New England. A robust mid-level disturbance along with multiple waves of surface low pressure then tracked along the front during the day. Over southern New England and southern New York, a uniquely favorable environment of high wind shear and high instability contributed to a significant severe weather outbreak. Further south, shear and forcing were a bit weaker. However, thunderstorms eventually progressed southward into the mid-Atlantic, fueled in part by outflow from storms to the north. Some of these storms became severe and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were downed in the Bethlehem area. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed during the evening hours ahead of a cold front moving through the Ohio Valley. The thunderstorms continued into the early morning hours of the 29th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A car was stuck in high water near the intersection of Russell Road and Kuther Road. High water was also reported on numerous roads throughout the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed during the evening hours ahead of a cold front moving through the Ohio Valley. The thunderstorms continued into the early morning hours of the 29th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High water was reported on a few streets in Urbana, including along Jefferson Avenue and Powell Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed through the early morning hours as a low pressure system moved through the Ohio Valley. Some of the storms produced locally heavy rainfall amounts of 2 to 3 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High water required a water rescue near Daly Road and Southshore Drive.

Observations showed gusts of 40 to 60 mph throughout the Bay Area and Central Coast. These winds fueled multiple grass and vegetation fires throughout the area, some of which prompted evacuations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Altamont RAWS station reported gusts between 40 and 61 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Two swimmers were rescued in the ocean at Ocean Beach in San Francisco in early June. One was brought in by a surfer the other was later pulled out but went into cardiac arrest. He later died at the hospital.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two swimmers were rescued in the ocean at Ocean Beach in San Francisco in early June. One was brought in by a surfer the other was later pulled out but went into cardiac arrest. He later died at the hospital https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2020/06/04/man-dies-after-being-rescued-from-surf-at-ocean-beach/.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Two children were playing in the water at Ocean Beach and were swept out in a rip current. Their parents went in after them and were also swept out to sea in the same rip current. All four were rescued by a lifeguard and some surfers. Two additional children were also caught in a rip current that same day at Ocean Beach and needed to be rescued.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two children were playing in the water at Ocean Beach and were swept out in a rip current. Their parents went in after them and were also swept out to sea in the same rip current. All four were rescued by a lifeguard and some surfers. Exact time of incident unknown.

A rain gauge near the intersection of the Sawgrass Expressway with the Florida Turnpike reported 2.21 inches of rain had fallen, with around three quarters of an inch of that falling in the last hour.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moving across the state brought fast moving thunderstorms that brought strong winds to many areas across western and central Wyoming. Some of the more notable wind gusts included 73 mph at Red Canyon and 66 mph along Interstate 25 in southern Johnson County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 59 mph wind gust was recorded at the Natrona County Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level trough located north of the an area and abundant moisture combined with local and diurnal effects to generate afternoon showers and thunderstorms across the northwestern quadrant of Puerto Rico. Very heavy rainfall occurred, particularly in the urban areas of Arecibo, where accumulations in excess of 3-4 inches were observed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Residence flooded in Calle O near a community center.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant northerly swell from distant Hurricane Teddy, which tracked well north of the area, resulting in coastal flooding across some areas along the north coast of PR.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor coastal flooding reported on Road PR-187 near Chatarra Beach in Loiza.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Increasing moisture and instability ahead of an approaching cold front produced a severe thunderstorm and damaging winds on Lake Louise in Dickinson County on the evening of the 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: There was a public report of a severe thunderstorm at a cottage on Lake Louise.  The cottage sustained roof and chimney damage when a 18-inch diameter 50+ foot high spruce tree was uprooted by thunderstorm winds.  The storm also sheared off a flagpole and damaged a kayak, paddleboard and heavy patio furniture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed ahead of a shortwave and a couple became severe. Wind gusts of over 58 mph were recorded in Fremont and Natrona Counties, with the strongest wind gust of 67 mph at Red Canyon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The wind sensor at Red Canyon had a maximum wind gust of 67 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Automated stream gauges indicated flash flooding developed along the Tuckasegee River in the Bryson City area after more than 4 inches of rain fell over the region in about 24 hours, with much of that falling during the morning of the 6th. Multiple roads and businesses flooded around the downtown area, including along Gibson Ave, Island St, Everett St, Carringer St, and Collins St. Although the rate of rise slowed during the afternoon as rain began to taper off, minor flooding persisted along the Tuckasegee through the evening hours of the 6th.

Some of the main impacts were in Cramerton, where Riverside Dr was inundated, as were several parking lots. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Timber Mountain (TMBN2), Elevation 9000 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet end to the 3rd week of June and continued moderate to heavy rainfalls into the middle of the 4th week of June caused rivers across the eastern portions of the Des Moines CWA to swell and reach flood stage from as little as a few hours near Tama to a few days around Cedar Falls, Waterloo, and Hudson.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Cedar River at Waterloo crested at 15.54 feet at 0415 UTC on June 25th. Flood stage is 13.0 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of weakening showers and thunderstorms tracked through east-central Wisconsin during the late morning hours.  There was a microburst with one of the storms in Outagamie County, which downed some trees, power lines, and large branches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds downed small to medium trees, large branches, and power lines in Freedom. The time of this event is an estimate based on radar data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front aided in lofting a focused pool of moisture into South Florida. As the Gulf breeze developed, the abundant moisture combined with enhanced lifting to result in a few strong thunderstorms that produced flooding associated with heavy rainfall in Collier County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Photos via Twitter show street flooding in Naples near 2nd ave North and 9th street North.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnant circulation from tropical storm Cristobal combined with strong, negatively tilted phasing shortwave disturbance moved across the area providing strong synoptic winds ahead of the storms. Strong, dynamic cold front initiated storms just after the noon hour with damaging winds, hail, and heavy rain observed during the afternoon. Strong post frontal drying within fierce mid level dry intrusion yielded 40 to 60 mph wind gusts and blowing dust late afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Roof damage with a dozen or so shingles bent or missing.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front passed through the area. Despite limited instability, there was a strong wind field aloft along with steep low-level lapse rates. This resulted in some damaging wind gusts with showers and thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were reported down in the vicinity of MD-97 New Washington Road and Bartholow Road in the Sykesville area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front along with an upper level disturbance approached the mid-Atlantic on August 29. Shear increased as these systems approached. A very humid air mass was in place across the mid-Atlantic, which contributed to considerable cloud cover over the region for much of the day. This limited instability. The approaching front did initiate scattered to widespread convection. Heavy rain ended up being the greater threat than severe weather due to marginal instability, but a few reports of damaging winds were received with stronger storms over Pennsylvania.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down in the area. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moisture laden storm system tracked along a old cold front from the the Gulf of Mexico up across NY and VT. On Saturday, January 11th, the front was positioned across southern Canada with temperatures in the 50s/60s across NY. As the front slowly progressed south into northern NY during the evening, moderate to heavy rain fell across the region. Shortly after midnight of January 12th, the cold front slipped south of the Adirondacks with rain changing to freezing rain across the St. Lawrence and northern Champlain Valleys. ||Widespread 1/4 to 1/2 inches of ice accretion with locally up to 3/4 inch was observed along the international border, resulting in hazardous travel and scattered power outages.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accretion  reports of 1/4 to 1/2 inch with locally up to 3/4 inch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: EM reported North Muddy Creek and/or a tributary overflowed its banks and inundated Gilbert Byrd Rd in the vicinity of the I-40 underpass. Four to five inches of rain fell across the area in about 24 hours, with about half of that falling during the morning of the 6th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rainfall tapered off across McDowell County through the afternoon of the 6th, flooding persisted along North Muddy Creek and its tributaries, with Gilbert Byrd Rd remaining inundated into the evening hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of strong storms moved across central Florida, producing strong wind gusts along the coasts of Brevard and Martin Counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm, moist airmass was in place across the region ahead of a potent January weather system. Ample wind energy also was present, which not only helped bring damaging winds with severe storms but also allowed for strong gradient winds to occur ahead of an eastward advancing squall line. Severe weather occurred in the early morning hours of January 11th and continued across the ArkLaMiss region before noon, resulting in widespread wind damage as well as some tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down on a house along North 34th Avenue.

A tree was blown down on Military Road. A tree was blown down onto a house near Columbus. A tree was blown down along Woodridge Place and a carport was destroyed near New Hope.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep upper-level trough moved slowly across the central and eastern U.S. bringing abundant moisture northward and combined with a complex frontal boundary with several waves of low pressure to bring repeated rounds of heavy rainfall. Rainfall totals for the 72-hour period ending at 700 AM EST on February 7th ranged from 2 to 6 inches with isolated higher amounts along the Blue Ridge Mountains, but most of the rain fell within a 48-hour period. Numerous NWS Cooperative stations reported record one-day February rainfall amounts ending on the morning of February 6th and/or the 7th and numerous two-day all-time February records were also set. Some flash flooding occurred early during the event as higher rates of rainfall were embedded within the overall rain pattern. Numerous rivers and streams flooded, some reaching crests in the 25- to 50-year flood recurrence interval and many roads were flooded with significant damage to some infrastructure.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several roads were damaged by floodwaters in Surry County and flooding was reported along the Fisher River and Stewart's Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep upper-level trough moved slowly across the central and eastern U.S. bringing abundant moisture northward and combined with a complex frontal boundary with several waves of low pressure to bring repeated rounds of heavy rainfall. Rainfall totals for the 72-hour period ending at 700 AM EST on February 7th ranged from 2 to 6 inches with isolated higher amounts along the Blue Ridge Mountains, but most of the rain fell within a 48-hour period. Numerous NWS Cooperative stations reported record one-day February rainfall amounts ending on the morning of February 6th and/or the 7th and numerous two-day all-time February records were also set. Some flash flooding occurred early during the event as higher rates of rainfall were embedded within the overall rain pattern. Numerous rivers and streams flooded, some reaching crests in the 25- to 50-year flood recurrence interval and many roads were flooded with significant damage to some infrastructure.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The NWS Cooperative station at Yanceyville 4 SE (YAVN7) set a daily February rainfall record of 2.38 inches for the 24-hour period ending 700 AM EST on February 7th. The previous February record was 1.98 inches on Feb. 16, 1998 (complete data since 1997). The station also set a February two-day record with 2.52 inches ending at 700 AM on the 7th, eclipsing the 2.48 inches on February 15-16, 1998.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-stationary frontal boundary was located near the border region of the mid-Atlantic and New England for much of the day on August 28. South of the front, a hot and humid air mass developed. In addition, a fast moving approaching shortwave disturbance caused shear to increase, creating an environment of moderate to strong shear and instability as well as high moisture. Forcing from the shortwave caused widespread convection to develop by early to mid afternoon. Significant storm organization occurred, particularly in association with a line of storms that impacted portions of Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and northern Delmarva. This mesoscale convective system (MCS) produced widespread wind damage, with a few other storms across the region also producing damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were downed near Evergreen Dr. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm, moist airmass was in place across the region ahead of a potent January weather system. Ample wind energy also was present, which not only helped bring damaging winds with severe storms but also allowed for strong gradient winds to occur ahead of an eastward advancing squall line. Severe weather occurred in the early morning hours of January 11th and continued across the ArkLaMiss region before noon, resulting in widespread wind damage as well as some tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down around Pachuta. This included some that blocked I-59 south and multiple trees that were blown onto I-59 between Enterprise and Pachuta. Several power lines were also blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across western North Carolina from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in rather widespread flash flooding. Isolated tornadoes also developed during this time across the Piedmont. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches resulted in flooding persisting along some main stem rivers and larger streams well into the 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotter reported multiple trees blown down in the area bound by Highway 3, Old Airport Road, and Highway 73.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: County comms reported flash flooding developed across portions of Caldwell County after 4 to 5.5 inches of rain fell in about 24 hours with much of that falling during the morning of the 6th. Multiple roads were closed due to a combination of poor drainage in urban areas and due to small stream flooding.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Newspaper reported flash flooding developed across central Alexander County after 4 to 5.5 inches of rain fell across the county in around 24 hours, with much of that falling during the morning and early afternoon of the 6th. Multiple tributaries of the Lower Little River overflowed their banks and flooded adjacent roads. These included Muddy Fork, which inundated Old Wilkesboro Rd just north of Taylorsville, Stirewalt Creek which flooded Heavenly Acres Rd, and Glade Creek which flooded Millersville Rd and Paul Pane Store Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front along with an upper level disturbance approached the mid-Atlantic on August 29. Shear increased as these systems approached. A very humid air mass was in place across the mid-Atlantic, which contributed to considerable cloud cover over the region for much of the day. This limited instability. The approaching front did initiate scattered to widespread convection. Heavy rain ended up being the greater threat than severe weather due to marginal instability, but a few reports of damaging winds were received with stronger storms over Pennsylvania.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed onto wires along Berger Creek Rd. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong mid-level trough protruded into the Desert Southwest, which led to strong Santa Ana winds and very dry weather conditions. This led to destructive wildfires and damaging winds across Southern California starting December 2nd and beyond.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Cal Fire reports the start of the Bond Fire from a house fire on the night of December 2nd. Gusty Santa Ana winds aided in the scorching of 6,686 acres in the Santa Ana foothills near Santiago and Silverado Canyons. The area experienced multiple evacuation warnings and road closures, 21 structures damaged and 31 structures destroyed, along with 2 firefighter injuries.

CZ_NAME: LOS ANGELES COUNTY MOUNTAINS EXCLUDING THE SANTA MONICA RANGE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful late-season storm moved across Southwestern California. The storm brought significant rainfall to the area with totals up to 3.00 inches reported. In the mountains, snow levels dropped to around 4500 feet and significant snowfall was reported at elevations above 5000 feet. Along with the snow, gusty southerly winds impacted the area with gusts up to 50 MPH.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snowfall blanketed the mountains of Los Angeles county. At the resort level (around 7000 feet), snowfall totals of 8 to 16 inches were reported. Additionally, southerly winds, gusting to 50 MPH, were observed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long-lived quasi-linear convective system moved into northwest Alabama between 6 and 9 AM, and gradually tracked east across the remainder of north Alabama through the midday and early afternoon hours.  In advance of the line, strong southerly winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 45 mph were reported.  In some cases, trees and power lines were knocked down with these non-thunderstorm winds.  The line of thunderstorms yielded numerous reports of thunderstorm wind damage, including trees and power lines being knocked down, along with some structural damage.  A few weather stations measured wind gusts of 58 mph or higher as well.  Storm surveys revealed 3 separate tornadoes: 1 EF0 and 1 EF1 in Cullman County,  and 1 EF2 in Marshall County.  Intense rainfall in a short period of time resulted in a few reports of brief flash flooding in northwest Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms winds damaged the Section Highs School score board.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unusually high levels of moisture for early February combined with a slow-moving frontal system to produce an extended period of moderate to heavy rainfall across northeast Georgia from the morning of the 5th until the early morning hours of the 7th. Intense rain rates associated with bands of heavy rain showers and embedded thunderstorms developing along the front during the morning and afternoon of the 7th resulted in flash flooding. Total rainfall of 3 to 6 inches occurred across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although rainfall tapered off across Rabun County throughout the afternoon, high water conditions persisted across the county due to runoff from the excessive rainfall earlier in the day.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long-lived quasi-linear convective system moved into northwest Alabama between 6 and 9 AM, and gradually tracked east across the remainder of north Alabama through the midday and early afternoon hours.  In advance of the line, strong southerly winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 45 mph were reported.  In some cases, trees and power lines were knocked down with these non-thunderstorm winds.  The line of thunderstorms yielded numerous reports of thunderstorm wind damage, including trees and power lines being knocked down, along with some structural damage.  A few weather stations measured wind gusts of 58 mph or higher as well.  Storm surveys revealed 3 separate tornadoes: 1 EF0 and 1 EF1 in Cullman County,  and 1 EF2 in Marshall County.  Intense rainfall in a short period of time resulted in a few reports of brief flash flooding in northwest Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was knocked down at this location. Time estimated by radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another very dry month with little in the way of monsoon moisture worsened drought conditions across southwest and south-central New Mexico. Some areas around the Gila region were placed into Exceptional(D4) drought conditions while most other areas were at least in Severe(D2) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme(D3) drought conditions were located over the southwest portion of the zone with Severe(D2) conditions across the northeast.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong mid-level trough in split flow moved out of the southwestern U.S. on the morning of April 12, and phased with a strong northern stream trough across the northern Plains by April 13. Intense low pressure developed across the central Plains and moved into the Great Lakes, with a strong frontogenetic band of precipitation from Nebraska to Minnesota. Convective instability produced some spotty thunder along with the rain changing to snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totaled 2.0 inches 8 miles southeast of Hendricks. Winds gusted at times to 30 to 39 mph near Lake Benton between 0100 and 1000CST, with visibility frequently as low as one-half mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Isaias moved between Grand Bahama and Southeast Florida in the morning of August 2. Isaias tracked north, moving nearly parallel to the eastern Florida coast over the next 24-36 hours, making its closest approach when the center was approximately 36 miles east-southeast of Fort Pierce Inlet. Isaias produced a short duration of tropical storm force winds, with numerous gusts to tropical storm force in rain bands over the Atlantic coastal waters. These winds drove seas of at least 15 to 19 feet.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A short duration of sustained tropical storm winds impacted the coastal waters, with most of the tropical storm conditions experienced in the passing rain bands of Tropical Storm Isaias. These winds lasted from late evening August 2 to mid morning August 3.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Isaias moved between Grand Bahama and Southeast Florida in the morning of August 2. Isaias tracked north, moving nearly parallel to the eastern Florida coast over the next 24-36 hours, making its closest approach when the center was approximately 36 miles east-southeast of Fort Pierce Inlet. Outer rain bands on the western side of Isaias's circulation moved onshore of the east-central Florida coast producing sustained tropical storm force winds along the barrier islands, and gusts to tropical storm force west of the Intracoastal Waterway. There were no direct or indirect tropical storm-related fatalities. Tropical Storm Isaias produced minor beach erosion from elevated tide levels of approximately 1 foot above predicted tide values.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Martin County, sustained tropical storm force winds affected the barrier islands, with gusts to tropical storm force in squalls through much of the remainder of the county from early morning through late afternoon August 2. The highest sustained wind was measured at House of Refuge in Stuart (48 mph from the east at 0654LST on August 2) and the peak gust was also House of Refuge in Stuart (52 mph from the east at 0733LST on August 2).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong mid-level trough in split flow moved out of the southwestern U.S. on the morning of April 12, and phased with a strong northern stream trough across the northern Plains by April 13. Intense low pressure developed across the central Plains and moved into the Great Lakes, with a strong frontogenetic band of precipitation from Nebraska to Minnesota. Convective instability produced some spotty thunder along with the rain changing to snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totaled 4.0 inches at Edgerton. Winds at Pipestone gusted frequently from 30 to 35 mph, and as high as 40 mph between 0200 and 1200CST, with visibilities less than a mile, and frequently as low as one-quarter to one-half mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Powerful Hurricane Laura struck the Gulf Coast on August 26, 2020. The remnants of Laura moved through the Mid-South on August 27th and August 28th. The first band of showers and thunderstorms tracked across eastern Arkansas during the evening hours of August 27th causing wind damage and a half dozen weak tornadoes. An additional band of showers and thunderstorms developed across north Mississippi during the morning hours of August 28th as the system was departing. A weak morning tornado was reported near Oxford followed by a couple of incidents of wind damage over northeast Mississippi during the afternoon and isolated flash flooding later that evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado developed north of Cash and moved northwest.  The tornado pulled metal panels from an airplane hangar west of Highway 18.  The tornado damaged the roof of a home and uprooted trees along Highway 91 southeast of Egypt.  Trees were uprooted in Egypt, and the tornado dissipated as it moved through the community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Ormond Beach man was pulled out of the surf after struggling in a rip current at Ormond Beach. Beach Safety personnel performed life-saving measures but the man was pronounced dead at the hospital.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 47-year-old Ormond Beach man was pulled out of the surf after struggling in a rip current. The man entered the water with a female companion in an unguarded area near the 1200 block of north Ormond Beach around 1500LST. Another person that came to the beach with the victim saw both the man and woman struggling in the water and called 9-1-1. Beach Safety personnel stated the man was unresponsive when they got him out of the water. Lifesaving measures were initiated but the man was pronounced dead at the hospital. The woman that was with him was assisted safely from the water.

Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Utah during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of eastern Utah and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought expanded slightly further north to encompass the majority of the northern tier of the area by the end of September. Elsewhere, the extreme drought persisted across all but the far southeast portion of the zone which worsened to the exceptional (D4) category by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abnormally cold air filtered into western Colorado in the wake of an arctic cold front. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An abnormally strong and cold low pressure system and associated cold front dropped south across the Northern Rockies and into the Four Corners. The low remained quasi-stationary for about a day before lifting northeast into the Plains. This system produced widespread showers of rain in the lower elevations and snow in the mountains, though the cold front dropped snow levels to approximately 7000 feet. Additionally, high winds led to not only reduced visibility in blowing snow, but also numerous downed trees and power outages in some areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant blowing and drifting snow occurred across the region as winds gusted up to 50 to 60 MPH. A trained spotter measured 6.6 inches of snow 32 miles west-northwest of Maybell. Additionally, numerous power poles were knocked down between the spotter's location and the Utah border.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An abnormally strong and cold low pressure system and associated cold front dropped south across the Northern Rockies and into the Four Corners. The low remained quasi-stationary for about a day before lifting northeast into the Plains. This system produced widespread showers of rain in the lower elevations and snow in the mountains, though the cold front dropped snow levels to approximately 7000 feet. Additionally, high winds led to not only reduced visibility in blowing snow, but also numerous downed trees and power outages in some areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 8 to 12 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts up to 15 inches estimated at the Upper Taylor SNOTEL site. CoCoRaHS observers in and around Crested Butte measured 5 to 8 inches of snow. Additionally, the wet, heavy snow and strong winds led to numerous downed power lines and trees in South Crested Butte.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began in far northern Richland Parish east of the intersection of LA Highways 134 and 183. It crossed into southwestern West Carroll Parish, crossing Fusilier Rd, Gwin Rd, LA Highway 134, Duckworth Rd, and Sharplin Rd before crossing and ending just northeast of Waller Rd. Along the path, several trees were uprooted and multiple irrigation pivots were flipped. The total path length was 6.18 miles. The maximum estimated winds of the tornado occurred in West Carroll Parish at 105 mph. The maximum width was 700 yards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass was in place across the region as a frontal boundary was stalled across the central portions of the ArkLaMiss region. Severe thunderstorms moved across central and southern portions of the area during the afternoon and evening hours of the 19th. A supercell thunderstorm developed and moved across portions of the Pine Belt and brought a violent tornado across the region, for the second time in as many weeks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A swath of hail fell across portions of Yazoo County. Half dollar size hail fell across Vaughn while hail up to quarter size fell near Benton.

An early-season Nor'Easter produced anywhere from 6 inches of snow and sleet in the Lower Susquehanna Valley up to 30 inches of snow in parts of Tioga County. Widespread travel impacts were observed, and it was the heaviest snowfall from a single event that many central Pennsylvania locations had seen in a few years.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 17 to 32 inches of snow across Tioga County from December 16-17, 2020.

Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Brookside Road was closed at Buckeye Road in Lower Macungie Township due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures were experienced in southeast Arizona from July 29th through August 1st. Many locations approached or exceeded 110 degrees and set new daily record high temperatures. The Pima County Medical Examiner confirmed that heat was the primary cause of death for two adult males on the Tohono O'odham Nation on July 30th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures 7 to 16 degrees above normal occurred in the lower elevations of southeast Arizona, causing the High Heat Risk category, which was attained July 29 through July 31, to continue on August 1.  High temperatures on August 1 included 111 degrees at Picacho and Fort Thomas; 108 at Ajo, Green Valley (tie) and Willcox (record); and 105 (tie) at Douglas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across most of northern and central Virginia where the growing season was in effect.

Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across eastern West Virginia where the growing season was in effect.

Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across eastern West Virginia where the growing season was in effect.

A diffuse surface trough axis was north of the Altamaha River basin with very high dew pts in the low/mid 70s across the entire forecast area south of the boundary. The 12z|JAX RAOB showed less deep layer moisture (PWAT 1.6 inches) and stronger SW steering flow across the entire area from 10-15 kts south of I-10 across NE FL to 20 kts across our SE GA zones. There was drier air in the low/mid levels where the steepest lapse rates were near 6.8 C/km between 790 mb and 617 mb roughly. SE GA 0-6 km bulk shear was 20-25 kts. Ingredients favored pulse strong to severe storms with gusty downburst winds the main hazard.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A home was struck by lightning near Blanding Blvd and Doctors Inlet. The cost of damage was unknown but estimated for Storm Data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Coastal heavy rainfall occurred as low pressure drifted northward offshore of the NE Florida Atlantic coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three inches of rainfall occurred near Watson Road near St. Augustine Shores in 2.5 hours. Minor flooding was reported on U.S. Highway 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Coastal heavy rainfall occurred as low pressure drifted northward offshore of the NE Florida Atlantic coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 24 hr rainfall total of 5.5 inches was measured in Princess Place Estates. A couple of other gauges in the area measured 4.5 to 5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Sea breeze storms caused a lightning structure fire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lighting caused a house fire in Mandarin along Grand Lakes Drive South. The time of the damage was based on NLDN data. The cost of damage was unknown but estimated for the inclusion of the event in Storm Data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dry period with near critical relative humidity were near 30% with light SW winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Florida Forest Service reported a wildfire about 150 acres in the Juniper Wilderness of the Ocala NF. The time given was the approximate start time of the fire.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought continues across two locations in Micronesia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wotje remains in  Severe Drought (D2). Near-adequate rainfall on Wotje has prevented any worsening drought conditions the last couple weeks. Wotje and Utirik have reverse osmosis units on site. Rainfall was also well above normal for Wotje last month with adequate rainfall so far this month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early-season Nor'Easter produced anywhere from 6 inches of snow and sleet in the Lower Susquehanna Valley up to 30 inches of snow in parts of Tioga County. Widespread travel impacts were observed, and it was the heaviest snowfall from a single event that many central Pennsylvania locations had seen in a few years.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 8 to 14 inches of snow across Bedford County from December 16-17, 2020.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures were experienced in southeast Arizona from July 29th through August 1st. Many locations approached or exceeded 110 degrees and set new daily record high temperatures. The Pima County Medical Examiner confirmed that heat was the primary cause of death for two adult males on the Tohono O'odham Nation on July 30th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures 7 to 16 degrees above normal occurred in the lower elevations of southeast Arizona, causing the High Heat Risk category, which was attained July 29 through July 31, to continue on August 1.  High temperatures on August 1 included 111 degrees at Picacho and Fort Thomas; 108 at Ajo, Green Valley (tie) and Willcox (record); and 105 (tie) at Douglas.

CZ_NAME: GORE AND ELK MOUNTAINS/CENTRAL MOUNTAIN VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An abnormally strong and cold low pressure system and associated cold front dropped south across the Northern Rockies and into the Four Corners. The low remained quasi-stationary for about a day before lifting northeast into the Plains. This system produced widespread showers of rain in the lower elevations and snow in the mountains, though the cold front dropped snow levels to approximately 7000 feet. Additionally, high winds led to not only reduced visibility in blowing snow, but also numerous downed trees and power outages in some areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across the area with 10 inches estimated at the Independence Pass SNOTEL site. CoCoRaHS observers near Redstone, Avon and Vail recorded 1 to 3 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 64 MPH was measured by the Windy Point automated weather station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across eastern West Virginia where the growing season was in effect.
Despite high pressure beginning to move offshore, the atmosphere still decoupled due to a light gradient, causing temperatures to drop below freezing over portions of western Maryland.

Despite high pressure beginning to move offshore, the atmosphere still decoupled due to a light gradient, causing temperatures to drop below freezing over portions of Virginia west of the Blue Ridge Mountains.

A very strong cold front passed through the area while a potent upper-level trough was positioned just to our west. Strong winds aloft were able to mix down in heavier showers and thunderstorms due to an unstable atmosphere. Low-level winds changing speed and direction with height combined with a thunderstorm to trigger an isolated tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down in the Laurel area.

An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and several large limbs were blown down in town.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail fell in Schlater that was just larger than quarters.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions worsened to the extreme (D3) category across the entirety of the forecast zone by the end of August.

On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began in northern Richland Parish along Goose Hollow Rd. It traveled northeastward crossing Lingefelt Rd and then Mitchiner Rd, where it crossed into southwestern West Carroll Parish. The tornado then crossed Guice Rd, then lifted along LA Highway 134 just east of the damage path of another tornado that was occurring simultaneously in the same area. Along the path, multiple trees were uprooted and an irrigation pivot was flipped. The total path length was 4.65 miles. The maximum estimated winds in West Carroll Parish were 80mph. The overall tornado was rated an EF1 with 100 mph winds. The maximum width of the tornado was 150 yards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an  EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down in the area with some roads blocked, including Highway 15.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation continued well-below normal across northwest Iowa, varying from 10 to 25 percent of normal in the far northwest corner, to around 50 percent of normal toward Ida Grove and Storm Lake. Temperatures were mainly near to slightly below normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought evolved to severe (D2) drought conditions early in the month. Rainfall of less than 50 percent of normal along with near normal temperatures contributed to the worsening short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 71 MPH was measured by the Bryson Canyon automated weather station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wildfire began from unknown causes 20 miles east-southeast of Moab.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Lackey Fan Fire began in early September 20 miles east-southeast of Moab from unknown causes. The fire grew to 100 acres before it was contained a day later.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold northwesterly flow set up overhead in the wake of a departing system. This, combined with clearing skies and light winds, led to freezing temperatures across northwest Colorado. Some valleys saw their season-ending freeze with this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Overnight lows ranged from 21 to 28 degrees with a low temperature of 23 degrees recorded at the Steamboat Springs/Bob Adams Field Airport. This was a season-ending freeze for the Upper Yampa River Basin.

CZ_NAME: UPPER GILA RIVER AND ARAVAIPA VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures were experienced in southeast Arizona from July 29th through August 1st. Many locations approached or exceeded 110 degrees and set new daily record high temperatures. The Pima County Medical Examiner confirmed that heat was the primary cause of death for two adult males on the Tohono O'odham Nation on July 30th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures 7 to 16 degrees above normal occurred in the lower elevations of southeast Arizona, causing the High Heat Risk category, which was attained July 29 through July 31, to continue on August 1.  High temperatures on August 1 included 111 degrees at Picacho and Fort Thomas; 108 at Ajo, Green Valley (tie) and Willcox (record); and 105 (tie) at Douglas.

CZ_NAME: UPPER GILA RIVER AND ARAVAIPA VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The human caused Light Fire started on August 28th on San Carlos Apache Tribe lands between Calva and Bylas in northwest Graham County.  The fire spread through salt cedar by strong winds and burned around 1000 acres before becoming contained August 31st. Fire suppression costs tallied $50,000.  Five homes were evacuated near Calva Road and several utility poles burned, but no homes were damaged.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The human caused Light Fire started on August 28th on San Carlos Apache Tribe lands between Calva and Bylas in northwest Graham County.  The fire spread through salt cedar by strong winds and burned around 1000 acres with nearly 500 foot high flames, before becoming contained August 31st. Fire suppression costs tallied $50,000.  Five homes were evacuated near Calva Road and several utility poles burned, but no homes were damaged. The fire burned under the Bylas bridge causing the bridge and Highway 70 to be closed for 16 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated thunderstorms developed over southeast Arizona during the afternoon.  One cluster of storms tracked north across western Pima County and downed power poles in Ajo.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds downed several power poles in Ajo, causing a power outage for about 100 customers for 2 to 3 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated thunderstorms developed and moved west across parts of southeast Arizona during the afternoon and evening. One storm produced a severe wind gust at Nogales Airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: KOLS ASOS at Nogales Airport measured a wind gust to 59 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed and moved southwest over southeast Arizona during the afternoon and evening. One storm produced wind damage in Amado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: KALK ASOS at Pioneer Field recorded a thunderstorm wind gust of 69 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of the western slope and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought worsened to the exceptional (D4) category across all but the northern portion of the zone by the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass was in place across the region as a frontal boundary was stalled across the central portions of the ArkLaMiss region. Severe thunderstorms moved across central and southern portions of the area during the afternoon and evening hours of the 19th. A supercell thunderstorm developed and moved across portions of the Pine Belt and brought a violent tornado across the region, for the second time in as many weeks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball size hail fell around the Westover area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A back door frontal boundary that brought higher moisture levels and scattered thunderstorms to northeast New Mexico on July 11, 2020 became stationary over the area through July 12, 2020. The combination of strong afternoon heating with abundant moisture and instability led to the development of a few more showers and thunderstorms over Union and Harding counties. A couple of these storms produced strong winds, hail, and heavy rainfall. Nickel size hail was reported near Capulin while another storm produced severe wind gusts of 70 mph near Mills.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel size hail reported near Capulin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the entirety of the forecast zone through the end of August.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong cold front passed through the area while a potent upper-level trough was positioned just to our west. Strong winds aloft were able to mix down in heavier showers and thunderstorms due to an unstable atmosphere. Low-level winds changing speed and direction with height combined with a thunderstorm to trigger an isolated tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was uprooted along Edmonson Avenue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving mid-level short wave swept through the region during the morning and early afternoon. With a fairly cold airmass in place over north Georgia and ample mid-level moisture, moderate to heavy snow quickly accumulated across a large portion of north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A COOP observer reported 1.8 inches of snow 7 miles northeast of Dallas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early-season Nor'Easter produced anywhere from 6 inches of snow and sleet in the Lower Susquehanna Valley up to 30 inches of snow in parts of Tioga County. Widespread travel impacts were observed, and it was the heaviest snowfall from a single event that many central Pennsylvania locations had seen in a few years.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 11 to 20 inches of snow across Potter County from December 16-17, 2020.

Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several water rescues took place in North Coventry Township.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado started in a wooded area just south of Frank Bell Road and snapped and uprooted multiple trees along field edges and as it crossed Highway 425. As the tornado crossed Frank Bell Road, a home sustained roof damage and a shed was destroyed with debris thrown across the field. Maximum winds were 100mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation continued well-below normal across northwest Iowa, varying from 10 to 25 percent of normal in the far northwest corner, to around 50 percent of normal toward Ida Grove and Storm Lake.  Temperatures were mainly near to slightly below normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions remained at severe (D2) levels through the month. Very warm and dry conditions at the start of the month were broken by rainfall of almost one inch at Le Mars and Remsen between September 8-12. However, very little precipitation and continued warm temperatures later in the month sustained the short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation continued well-below normal across southwest Minnesota, varying from 10 to 25 percent of normal.  Temperatures were mainly near to slightly below normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought evolved to severe (D2) drought conditions early in the month. Rainfall of less than 25 percent of normal along with near normal temperatures contributed to the worsening short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying low tracking northeast along the coast approached late on the 5th...crossed the Gulf of Maine and southeast Washington county overnight...then exited across the Maritimes during the 6th. Precipitation expanded across Downeast areas during the morning of the 5th and across the remainder of the region through the afternoon. Snow...heavy at times...then persisted across northern and west-central portions of the region into the evening of the 6th. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour occurred in heavier snow bands from late on the 5th through the early morning hours of the 6th. Warning criteria snow accumulations occurred through the  early morning hours of the 6th. Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches across northern and west-central portions of the region. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow along with significantly reduced visibilities and near blizzard conditions at times. Heavy wet snow and winds also brought down trees and power lines. Mixed precipitation and rain limited snow totals across Downeast areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 8 to 15 inches. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced extensive blowing and drifting snow with near blizzard conditions at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down along Highway 4.
