EVENT_NARRATIVE: PA Route 309 was closed at West Saucon Valley Road in Upper Saucon Township due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying low tracking northeast along the coast approached late on the 5th...crossed the Gulf of Maine and southeast Washington county overnight...then exited across the Maritimes during the 6th. Precipitation expanded across Downeast areas during the morning of the 5th and across the remainder of the region through the afternoon. Snow...heavy at times...then persisted across northern and west-central portions of the region into the evening of the 6th. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour occurred in heavier snow bands from late on the 5th through the early morning hours of the 6th. Warning criteria snow accumulations occurred through the  early morning hours of the 6th. Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches across northern and west-central portions of the region. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow along with significantly reduced visibilities and near blizzard conditions at times. Heavy wet snow and winds also brought down trees and power lines. Mixed precipitation and rain limited snow totals across Downeast areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 12 to 16 inches. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced extensive blowing and drifting snow with near blizzard conditions at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed and moved northeast across southeast Arizona during the afternoon and evening. One storm produced wind damage at Marana High School and another produced flash flooding over the Bighorn Fire burn scar.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of rain fell in less than an hour over the headwaters of the Bighorn Fire burn scar on the Santa Catalina Mountains. An 8 foot rise was noted along the Canada Del Oro Wash  at Rancho Solano upstream in Pinal County . Strong flows continued downstream into Pima County causing water to flow across Edwin Road.  Catalina St. Park Road was also closed due to flows in Sutherland Wash.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist back door front entered northeast New Mexico during the early morning hours of July 11, 2020. The combination of strong daytime heating and abundant moisture with northwest flow aloft led to the development of isolated showers and thunderstorms across the northeast plains. Several of these storms became strong with gusty winds, hail, heavy rainfall, and frequent lightning. Hail up to the size of quarters was reported with a storm that became severe over eastern San Miguel County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to the size of quarters fell near Bell Ranch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold northwesterly flow set up overhead in the wake of a departing system. This, combined with clearing skies and light winds, led to freezing temperatures across western Colorado. Some valleys saw their season-ending freeze with this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Overnight lows ranged from 30 to 32 degrees with a low temperature of 30 degrees recorded at the Durango-La Plata County Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold northwesterly flow set up overhead in the wake of a departing system. This, combined with clearing skies and light winds, led to freezing temperatures across western Colorado. Some valleys saw their season-ending freeze with this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Overnight lows ranged from 25 to 32 degrees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wildfire began, most likely from human causes, 4 miles north of Wolcott.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The 4 Eagle Fire began in late September 4 miles north of Wolcott east of Colorado Highway 131, most likely from human causes. The fire grew to 121 acres before it was contained a day later. It broke out on private land at 4 Eagle Ranch and destroyed a cabin shed, a UTV and a van.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Utah during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of eastern Utah and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the entirety of the zone through the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Utah during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of eastern Utah and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the far northern and the southern portions of the zone and worsened to the exceptional (D4) category across the central portion of the zone by the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early-season Nor'Easter produced anywhere from 6 inches of snow and sleet in the Lower Susquehanna Valley up to 30 inches of snow in parts of Tioga County. Widespread travel impacts were observed, and it was the heaviest snowfall from a single event that many central Pennsylvania locations had seen in a few years.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 5 to 10 inches of snow across Lebanon County from December 16-17, 2020.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Sea  breeze thunderstorms developed over a moist and unstable airmass. Cool mid level temperatures with 500 mb around -10 degC and modestly unstable lapse rates with dry air in the hail growth zone supported pulse severe storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Keystone Heights AWOS stationed measured a thunderstorm wind gust of 63 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A plume of high tropical moisture with PWAT over 2 inches was across the local area with fairly light WSW steering flow around 10 kts. This regime pushed the west coast sea breeze inland where it merge with the river breeze and east coast sea breeze near the St. Johns River basin and produced a few strong storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power line was damaged at 1028 County Road 13 South. The time of damage was based on radar. The cost of damage was estimated for inclusion of the event in Storm Data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A house along Mississippi Highway 18 near Wright Road had taken on water from recent heavy rain and flooding also occurred on Highway 18 near Cidero Road.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Owen Boone Road near MS Highway 13 was flooded from earlier heavy rainfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the majority of the forecast zone and expanded to include the few remaining portions of the zone by the end of August.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the far eastern portion of the zone and expanded to include the entirety of the forecast zone by the end of August.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an  EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A swath of downed trees along a narrow path consistent with tornado damage was noted on satellite imagery in an area of the Delta National Forest. This area was inaccessible to damage survey teams due to backwater flooding. A tornadic debris signature was also noted on radar with this storm.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began just southwest of Whites Lane Road snapping a couple of trees. The tornado continued northeast and destroyed two outbuildings and a shed just southwest of Lake City. The tornado also snapped a couple of power poles along with several trees at this location. The tornado destroyed an outbuilding near the intersection of Highway 149 and Lake City Road. The tornado continued northeast near the Yazoo County Airport snapping a couple of trees. The tornado destroyed a home of off Carter Road, which was poorly anchored and was of wood construction. The tornado snapped several power poles off of Lake City Road and took the roof off of an outbuilding on Cato Road. This tornado ended just east of Yazoo Levee Road, snapping a few more trees. The maximum estimated winds with this tornado were 120 mph.

An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an  EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front which moved east across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado originally touched down in Clermont County at 21:50 EST and caused damage near Newtonsville. At 21:56 EST, the tornado moved into Brown County and later produced tree and structural damage near Lake Lorelei, with wind speeds of about 80 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front which crossed east through the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado touched down 3.5 miles east of the Mt. Zion area, on the western fringe of Williamstown Lake, along Peaceful Hollow Road. Several outbuildings and barns sustained roof damage, as well as some roof damage to homes.||The tornado then moved into Pendleton County at 21:50 EST and ended in Pendleton County near Milford Road at 22:07 EST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front which moved east across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado touched down in far southwestern Clinton County just west of SR-123. It moved east southeast across SR-123 into Brown County at 22:02 EST, before lifting just across the Brown County border.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: PA Route 100 was closed at Swamp Creek Road in Colebrookdale Township due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying low tracking northeast along the coast approached late on the 5th...crossed the Gulf of Maine and southeast Washington county overnight...then exited across the Maritimes during the 6th. Precipitation expanded across Downeast areas during the morning of the 5th and across the remainder of the region through the afternoon. Snow...heavy at times...then persisted across northern and west-central portions of the region into the evening of the 6th. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour occurred in heavier snow bands from late on the 5th through the early morning hours of the 6th. Warning criteria snow accumulations occurred through the  early morning hours of the 6th. Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches across northern and west-central portions of the region. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow along with significantly reduced visibilities and near blizzard conditions at times. Heavy wet snow and winds also brought down trees and power lines. Mixed precipitation and rain limited snow totals across Downeast areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 8 to 12 inches. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced extensive blowing and drifting snow with near blizzard conditions at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of the western slope and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the entirety of the forecast zone through the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of the western slope and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted across the eastern half of the zone and worsened to the exceptional (D4) category across the western half of the zone by the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of the western slope and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought persisted across the eastern and central portions of the zone and worsened to the exceptional (D4) category across the western portion of the zone by the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass was in place across the region as a frontal boundary was stalled across the central portions of the ArkLaMiss region. Severe thunderstorms moved across central and southern portions of the area during the afternoon and evening hours of the 19th. A supercell thunderstorm developed and moved across portions of the Pine Belt and brought a violent tornado across the region, for the second time in as many weeks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down onto a house and a camper along Doc Johnson Road near the intersection with Purvis to Columbia Road. Large tree limbs were also blown down in the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of stationary thunderstorms producing heavy rainfall over Dundy County Nebraska expanded south into Cheyenne County.  Rainfall amounts of over eight inches fell, with the highest amounts of rain occurring near the Nebraska border.  Multiple roads had sections washed out, some as deep as 10 ft or so.  Some farms in the northern part of the county were stranded due to all the roads leading out being washed out.  Water in the Republican River was running so fast and deep that trees were snapping.  One bridge in the county was damaged and another was washed out from the flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Most of the road damage from flooding occurred north of CR S, with the damage becoming more severe toward the Nebraska border. One bridge was partially damaged east of Highway 27 near CR Z. Another bridge was washed out at River Road and RS 115. A culvert was washed out on CR 19 between CR AA and CR BB. Near CR BB and CR 17 a barb wire fence was washed onto the road. Near CR 15 and CR V flood waters had washed a large tree onto the road. Near CR 2 the Republican River was out of its banks. Hackberry Creek was also flooding where it joined with the Republican River. Damage from the flooding is unknown due to the unknown number of sections of road washed out and the unknown acres of crop land flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms moved south into Northwest Kansas during the evening.  Wind gusts up to 60 MPH were recorded as the storms moved through, with the strongest gust occurring near St. Francis.  Hail up to two inches in diameter fell with these storms, with the largest hail reported near Herndon.  As the storms moved south their intensity declined.

An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down.

As it tracked over US 45 it snapped 6 metal high tension electrical poles, damaged a home, and snapped and uprooted several trees. The EF-2 tornado continued to track near Magnolia Drive, where it snapped several trees and damaged 4 chicken houses. It weakened and lifted as it approached Baldwyn Road. The maximum estimated wind speed was 125 mph.

This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an  EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous large branches were broken.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a home in the Cornerstone Subdivision.  This resulted in a house fire that caused substantial damage.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down onto houses along Second, Third and Fourth streets. Trees were also blown down along LA Highway 921, near the intersection of LA highways 913 and 916, and along Ratcliff Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) to severe (D2) drought conditions worsened to the extreme (D3) category across the entirety of the forecast zone by the end of August.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought conditions worsened to the extreme (D3) category across the majority of the forecast zone by the end of August and to the severe (D2) category across the far northwest portion of the zone.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure brought strong winds to several counties across the area, though no damage was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Station SE West Wendover (Union Pacific 994), Elevation 4408 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass was in place across the region as a frontal boundary was stalled across the central portions of the ArkLaMiss region. Severe thunderstorms moved across central and southern portions of the area during the afternoon and evening hours of the 19th. A supercell thunderstorm developed and moved across portions of the Pine Belt and brought a violent tornado across the region, for the second time in as many weeks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down onto Sullivan Drive near Highway 49.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 62 mph wind gust was measured at Bobby L Chain Municipal Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms moved south into Northwest Kansas during the evening.  Wind gusts up to 60 MPH were recorded as the storms moved through, with the strongest gust occurring near St. Francis.  Hail up to two inches in diameter fell with these storms, with the largest hail reported near Herndon.  As the storms moved south their intensity declined.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Estimated time of report from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist and unstable airmass was present across the ArkLaMiss region during the afternoon of the 8th, which facilitated storm development across the region. Storms became severe and brought damaging winds but mainly hail to portions of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down along Harris Road.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began along Highway 18 to the southeast of Rose Hill in Jasper County where it uprooted some trees. It then tracked northeast and crossed into Clarke County. Here it crossed I-59 and snapped or uprooted trees along Highway 513 as it tracked toward Enterprise. The tornado then crossed County Road 360/Helms Road before turning slightly to the north, causing tree damage and some roof damage along County Road 513/Highway 11. This continued before ending along County Road 370 to the northwest of Enterprise. The maximum estimated winds were 105 mph in Clarke County. Total width was 985 yards (0.56 miles) in Clarke County. Total path length was 8.87 miles.

On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and power lines were blown down along Highway 61 near Valley Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Abnormally dry (D0) to moderate (D1) drought conditions worsened to the extreme (D3) category across the southern and central portions of the forecast zone by the end of August and to the severe (D2) category across the northern tier of the zone.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across most of northern and central Virginia where the growing season was in effect.

Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across most of northern and central Virginia where the growing season was in effect.
Rainfall of 25 to 50 percent of normal during July, following 50 to 75 percent of normal during June led to the development of severe short-term drought conditions over much of northwest Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought evolved to severe (D2) drought conditions by late month. Rainfall of less than 50 percent of normal along with above normal temperatures contributed to the worsening short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation of 25 to 50 percent of normal along with above normal temperatures led to worsening of drought conditions across northwest Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions continued through the month. Rainfall of less than 50 percent of normal along with above normal temperatures sustained the short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation continued well-below normal across northwest Iowa, varying from 10 to 25 percent of normal in the far northwest corner, to around 50 percent of normal toward Ida Grove and Storm Lake.  Temperatures were mainly near to slightly below normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions remained at severe (D2) levels through the month. Very warm and dry conditions at the start of the month were broken by rainfall of between one-half and one inch at Rock Valley and Sioux Center between September 8-12. However, very little precipitation and continued warm temperatures later in the month sustained the short-term agricultural drought. Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving mid-level short wave swept through the region during the morning and early afternoon. With a fairly cold airmass in place over north Georgia and ample mid-level moisture, moderate to heavy snow quickly accumulated across a large portion of north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An amateur radio operator reported 3.5 inches of snow 2 miles north-northwest of Jasper. A COOP observer reported 3 inches of snow 1 mile north-northwest of Jasper and a CoCoRaHS observer reported 2 inches of snow 7 miles northeast of Nelson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms moved south into Northwest Kansas during the evening.  Wind gusts up to 60 MPH were recorded as the storms moved through, with the strongest gust occurring near St. Francis.  Hail up to two inches in diameter fell with these storms, with the largest hail reported near Herndon.  As the storms moved south their intensity declined.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread flash flooding occurred across the city of Jackson. There was also significant flooding along Torrey Pines Drive near Byram, as well as along Woodell Drive near Forest Hill.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado began in far southeastern Catahoula Parish south of Larto Lake. It snapped several hardwood trees along Moody Road before crossing the Black River into Concordia Parish. Here it continued to snap hardwood trees along the banks of the river as well as when it crossed Red River Levee Road and Louisiana Highway 909. A mobile home also suffered minor roof damage, siding damage and loss of a metal awning. The tornado moved across a field before it ended along Louisiana Highway 129. Total path length was 4.01 miles. Maximum width of the tornado was one half of a mile. The maximum estimated winds were 110 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: During the late evening, a severe thunderstorm was responsible for an extensive swath of significant damage across several counties in the southern portion of the NWS Jackson service area. The main corridor of focused and higher end wind damage was across southern Copiah to far southern Simpson, as well as all of northern sections of Lawrence, Jefferson Davis and Covington counties before dissipating across northwest Jones County. Based on a NWS damage survey of portions of this swath, along with accounts and assessments from local Emergency Managers, significant wind speeds across this swath ranged between 80 and 100 mph. Within the overall swath, there were generally 2 to 3 focused corridors, roughly running from west northwest to east southeast, where the greatest concentration of damage occurred. General dimensions of the swath can be described as roughly 80 miles long with a width of 6 to 8 miles where the greatest concentration of damage occurred. Damage across this large swath were primarily damaged trees and downed power lines. Tree damage was a combination of uprooted and snapped trees and was quite extensive and best characterized by hundreds of thousands of damaged trees. Downed power lines and broken poles were extensive as well across the swath. Additionally, many structures were damaged with degrees of damage from minor to major. All of this was due to a combination of the wind itself causing damage or by downed trees damaging the structure.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lightning strike ignited a wildfire 18 miles north of Grand Junction.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Pine Gulch Fire began at the end of July due to lightning 18 miles north of Grand Junction and grew to 139,007 acres before it was contained in mid September. The combination of drought-stressed vegetation, unseasonably hot weather and steep terrain led to weeks of active burning. Smoke columns were often visible from Grand Junction and the surrounding area as the wildfire exhibited extreme fire behavior. During the night of August 18, the fire grew quickly due to thunderstorm winds up to 40 mph for a three to four hour period. As a result, the fire increased by more than 30,000 acres that night. As of August 27, 2020 the Pine Gulch Fire became the largest wildfire in Colorado State history, surpassing the Hayman Fire that burned near Colorado Springs in the summer of 2002.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across most of northern and central Virginia where the growing season was in effect.

Canadian high pressure ushered in chilly conditions late on the 16th through the early morning of the 17th. Temperatures dropped below freezing across most of northern and central Virginia where the growing season was in effect.
Thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front which crossed east through the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado initially touched down 3.5 miles east of the Mt. Zion area, on the western fringe of Williamstown Lake, along Peaceful Hollow Road at 21:47 EST.||The tornado then moved into Pendleton County at 21:50 EST, with the first evidence of tornadic damage in Pendleton County occurring along Hogg Ridge Road. The tornado moved east-southeast, producing damage along its path that impacted West Highway 22, Morgan 4 Oaks Road, Liberty Ridge Road, U.S. 27, and McKinneysburg Road. Damage included the destruction of several barns as well as numerous trees and power poles being snapped or knocked down. The end of the damage occurred along Milford Road, where debris from a destroyed barn was thrown into an adjacent field. Based on this|damage, this tornado produced winds of around 100 mph, and was rated an EF-1 on the Enhanced Fujita Scale.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front which moved east across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado originally touched down in far southwestern Clinton County just west of SR-123 at 22:01 EST. It moved east southeast across SR-123 into Brown County at 23:02, lifting just after the county line.  As it moved across OH-123 numerous trees were knocked down and pole barns were damaged.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front passed through on the 9th. Stronger winds were aloft, and some were able to mix down in heavier showers and thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust in excess of 30 knots was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass was in place across the region as a frontal boundary was stalled across the central portions of the ArkLaMiss region. Severe thunderstorms moved across central and southern portions of the area during the afternoon and evening hours of the 19th. A supercell thunderstorm developed and moved across portions of the Pine Belt and brought a violent tornado across the region, for the second time in as many weeks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees were snapped,including one that fell onto a building. Damage was from straight line winds south of the tornado track.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A couple of trees were blown down, including one on Highway 15 near Deer Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A blustery northwest flow ushered in a Canadian air mass behind a cold front during the early morning of April 22nd. Temperatures dropped below freezing in some locations.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-0 tornado touched down along Morgantown Road just east of the Walthall County Line where a few large limbs were broken and a tree was uprooted in a field. It continued east through the Holly Springs community and uprooted or snapped the tops off of several trees along a narrow path. Several trees fell near a home on Molly Road. The widest area of damage occurred along Holly Springs Road near where several trees fell near a home and Holly Springs Baptist Church. It continued east toward MS Highway 587 where it blew a few trees down and snapped a few large limbs near a home. It dissipated shortly after crossing the highway. The maximum estimated winds were 85 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist and unstable airmass was present across the ArkLaMiss region during the afternoon of the 8th, which facilitated storm development across the region. Storms became severe and brought damaging winds but mainly hail to portions of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 58 mph wind gust was measured at Naval Air Station Meridian.

This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and power poles were damaged.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down on Huntington Hill Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wildfire began from human causes 1 mile east of Glenwood Springs.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Grizzly Creek Fire began in mid August from human causes 1 mile east of Glenwood Springs. It grew to a total of 32,631 acres before it was contained in mid December. As a result of the fire, major Interstate-70 was closed through Glenwood Canyon for more than a week which greatly impacted summer travel.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began in far southeastern Morehouse Parish near the intersection of Trails End Rd and Bingham Ranch Rd, crossing the Boeuf River into far northern Richland Parish, where it crossed LA Highway 585. It then crossed Wiles Rd into western West Carroll Parish again crossing LA Highway 585, Henry Jones Rd, and then LA Highway 585 for a third time. The tornado crossed Smith Rd, Clay Rd, and Clear Lake Rd before ending along Copes Rd. Along the path, a few homes sustained minor roof damage, a couple mobile homes received minor damage, a motor home was overturned, a couple sheds were damaged, and several trees were snapped or uprooted. The tornado was strongest as it crossed LA Highway 585 near the intersection of Self Rd where five utility poles were snapped, several trees were snapped or uprooted, and a home was damaged by a fallen tree. The tornado was rated EF2 overall with winds of 115mph with a max width of 700 yards. Total path length was 9.52 miles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation associated with developing low pressure along the Gulf Coast overspread Upstate South Carolina during the morning. Temperatures were cold enough in most areas for the precipitation to fall as snow. The snow, which was heavy at times quickly accumulated, especially across Oconee County, where heavy snowfall totals were realized by around noon. By the time the snow tapered off during early/mid afternoon, total accumulations generally ranged from 2 to 5 inches.

Precipitation associated with developing low pressure along the Gulf Coast overspread Upstate South Carolina during the morning. Temperatures were cold enough in most areas for the precipitation to fall as snow. The snow, which was heavy at times quickly accumulated, especially across Oconee County, where heavy snowfall totals were realized by around noon. By the time the snow tapered off during early/mid afternoon, total accumulations generally ranged from 2 to 5 inches.
Precipitation continued well-below normal, varying from 10 to 25 percent of normal, across southeast South Dakota. Temperatures were mainly near normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought evolved to severe (D2) drought conditions early in the month. Rainfall of less than 25 percent of normal along with near normal temperatures contributed to the worsening short-term agricultural drought.  Crop damage is an estimate from insured losses. Information provided by the United States Department of Agriculture.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold high pressure system arriving from the north, coinciding with the approach of a mid and upper level trough from the west allowed for winter weather to develop over central North Carolina.  As precipitation developed during the day on February 20, colder air continued to be advected into North Carolina courtesy of strong high pressure located over the Great Lakes. A brief mixture of rain and snow changed to snow as the precipitation spread east throughout central NC during the late afternoon and early evening. Temperatures were near or slightly above freezing during the late afternoon, limiting accumulations. Temperatures fell below freezing during the evening and the snow accumulated rapidly. By late evening, light snow was falling over much of central North Carolina. The snow ended shortly after midnight at most locations. Storm total snowfall amounts ranged between one and four inches, with most Triad and Triangle locations receiving between two and three inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from 3 to 5 inches across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several roads were closed due to flooding in Bethlehem.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moisture laden storm system tracked along a old cold front from the the Gulf of Mexico up across NY and VT. On Saturday, January 11th, the front was positioned across southern Canada with temperatures in the 50s/60s across NY. As the front slowly progressed south into northern NY during the evening, moderate to heavy rain fell across the region. Shortly after midnight of January 12th, the cold front slipped south of the Adirondacks with rain changing to freezing rain across the St. Lawrence and northern Champlain Valleys. ||Widespread 1/4 to 1/2 inches of ice accretion with locally up to 3/4 inch was observed along the international border, resulting in hazardous travel and scattered power outages.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall changed to freezing rain mixed with sleet, that produced up to 1/4-1/3 accumulation in the north.

CZ_NAME: PARADOX VALLEY / LOWER DOLORES RIVER BASIN
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of September. As a result, drought conditions persisted across the entirety of the western slope and worsened to the exceptional category in some areas by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The extreme (D3) drought worsened to the exceptional (D4) category across all but the far southern portion of the zone by the end of September.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southwest steering flow focus the dominant west coast sea breeze to converge with the east coast sea breeze during the afternoon and early evening east of the Highway 301 corridor toward the I-95 corridor. Convective ingredients including cool 500 mb temps of -10 to -11, ML Cape of near 1000 J/kg and a weak mid level short wave traversing the area overhead during peak sea breeze collisions created a few severe storms which produced large hail over NE FL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported in Yulee and east toward Barnwell Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse surface trough axis was north of the Altamaha River basin with very high dew pts in the low/mid 70s across the entire forecast area south of the boundary. The 12z|JAX RAOB showed less deep layer moisture (PWAT 1.6 inches) and stronger SW steering flow across the entire area from 10-15 kts south of I-10 across NE FL to 20 kts across our SE GA zones. There was drier air in the low/mid levels where the steepest lapse rates were near 6.8 C/km between 790 mb and 617 mb roughly. SE GA 0-6 km bulk shear was 20-25 kts. Ingredients favored pulse strong to severe storms with gusty downburst winds the main hazard.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down along Vic Davis Road near U.S. Highway 82. The time of damage was based on radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures were above normal and precipitation was below normal across much of Colorado during the month of August. As a result, drought conditions in southwest and west-central Colorado either persisted or worsened with the drought expanding north to encompass much of the western slope by the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Abnormally dry (D0) to moderate (D1) drought conditions worsened to the extreme (D3) category across the southern and central portions of the forecast zone by the end of August and to the severe (D2) category across the northern tier of the zone.

Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down in the Rayville area, including some that were blown down across roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: During the late evening, a severe thunderstorm was responsible for an extensive swath of significant damage across several counties in the southern portion of the NWS Jackson service area. The main corridor of focused and higher end wind damage was across southern Copiah to far southern Simpson, as well as all of northern sections of Lawrence, Jefferson Davis and Covington counties before dissipating across northwest Jones County. Based on a NWS damage survey of portions of this swath, along with accounts and assessments from local Emergency Managers, significant wind speeds across this swath ranged between 80 and 100 mph. Within the overall swath, there were generally 2 to 3 focused corridors, roughly running from west northwest to east southeast, where the greatest concentration of damage occurred. General dimensions of the swath can be described as roughly 80 miles long with a width of 6 to 8 miles where the greatest concentration of damage occurred. Damage across this large swath were primarily damaged trees and downed power lines. Tree damage was a combination of uprooted and snapped trees and was quite extensive and best characterized by hundreds of thousands of damaged trees. Downed power lines and broken poles were extensive as well across the swath. Additionally, many structures were damaged with degrees of damage from minor to major. All of this was due to a combination of the wind itself causing damage or by downed trees damaging the structure. In Simpson County, the strongest hit area was right along the southern border, where many trees were snapped or uprooted.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorms produced very strong wind gusts over parts of northern Jefferson,  Adams and northeast Denver counties.  Peak wind gusts included:  67 mph, 6.7 miles west-southwest of Rocky Mountain Metro Airport; 64 mph just east Rocky Mountain Metro Airport and at Denver International Airport; with a gust to 58 mph near Thornton.

Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: PA Route 841 was closed near Lewisville Road in Elk Township due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level ridge of high pressure over the southwestern part of the country brought a two-day heat wave to parts of Southern California with record breaking temperatures.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Some areas reported highs in the triple digits during this heat wave. The Campo COOP reported a high of 100 degrees on the 18th, breaking a daily record.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Residual 3 to 4 foot southeast to south swell on the ocean waters after the passage of low pressure to the south and east helped prevent water drainage from the Long Island south shore back bays. This in combination with unusually high astronomical tides associated with the full moon of the 7th led to isolated moderate coastal flooding along the south shore back bays of Nassau County during the morning high tide cycles of the 7th and 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The moderate coastal flood threshold of 6.2 ft MLLW was touched at the USGS tidal gauge at Hudson Bay at Freeport from 2020-05-08 20:54 EST to 2020-05-08 21:12 EST.

CZ_NAME: FIRE ISLAND INLET NY TO SANDY HOOK NJ OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front and a rigorous mid level shortwave triggered convective showers along with some embedded thunderstorms across the coastal waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A marine thunderstorm wind gust of 47 knots was measured at Breezy Point station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Isaias brought high winds, heavy rain, several tornadoes, and coastal flooding to the mid-Atlantic region, becoming the most impactful tropical cyclone to impact most of the region since Sandy in 2012. Flash flooding as a result of heavy rain caused two direct deaths from this event...one in Lehigh County and the other in Montgomery County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Interstate 78 was closed at the US Route 22 interchange in Upper Macungie Township due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving mid-level short wave swept through the region during the morning and early afternoon. With a fairly cold airmass in place over north Georgia and ample mid-level moisture, moderate to heavy snow quickly accumulated across a large portion of north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An amateur radio operator reported 6.5 inches of snow 1 mile northwest of Sequoyah Lake. the Gilmer County Emergency Manager reported 5.5 inches of snow in Ellijay and the public reported 4 inches of snow 3 miles west-northwest of Cherry Log.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying low tracking northeast along the coast approached late on the 5th...crossed the Gulf of Maine and southeast Washington county overnight...then exited across the Maritimes during the 6th. Precipitation expanded across Downeast areas during the morning of the 5th and across the remainder of the region through the afternoon. Snow...heavy at times...then persisted across northern and west-central portions of the region into the evening of the 6th. Snowfall rates of 1 to 2 inches per hour occurred in heavier snow bands from late on the 5th through the early morning hours of the 6th. Warning criteria snow accumulations occurred through the  early morning hours of the 6th. Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches across northern and west-central portions of the region. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow along with significantly reduced visibilities and near blizzard conditions at times. Heavy wet snow and winds also brought down trees and power lines. Mixed precipitation and rain limited snow totals across Downeast areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 14 inches. Wind gusts of 30 to 35 mph produced extensive blowing and drifting snow with near blizzard conditions at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front dropped temperatures quickly across northwestern Pennsylvania, changing a steady rain over to heavy snow in Warren County. This system produced 4 to 8 inches of snowfall across Warren County, along with flash-freeze conditions as temperatures quickly dropped below freezing behind the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As much as 8 inches of post-frontal snow fell over portions of Warren County from late on December 24 into December 25, along with flash-freezing conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold high pressure system arriving from the north, coinciding with the approach of a mid and upper level trough from the west allowed for winter weather to develop over central North Carolina.  As precipitation developed during the day on February 20, colder air continued to be advected into North Carolina courtesy of strong high pressure located over the Great Lakes. A brief mixture of rain and snow changed to snow as the precipitation spread east throughout central NC during the late afternoon and early evening. Temperatures were near or slightly above freezing during the late afternoon, limiting accumulations. Temperatures fell below freezing during the evening and the snow accumulated rapidly. By late evening, light snow was falling over much of central North Carolina. The snow ended shortly after midnight at most locations. Storm total snowfall amounts ranged between one and four inches, with most Triad and Triangle locations receiving between two and three inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from 2 to 4 inches across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southwest steering flow focus the dominant west coast sea breeze to converge with the east coast sea breeze during the afternoon and early evening east of the Highway 301 corridor toward the I-95 corridor. Convective ingredients including cool 500 mb temps of -10 to -11, ML Cape of near 1000 J/kg and a weak mid level short wave traversing the area overhead during peak sea breeze collisions created a few severe storms which produced large hail over NE FL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail occurred in Fernandina Beach.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mean layer WSW steering flow was light across NE which enable sea breezes and river breezes to converge over inland areas over an unstable airmass. Cool mid level temperatures at 500 mb ranged from -10 to -12 deg C. This cool air aloft combined with high diurnal instability produced a few strong to severe storms with hail across NE FL. Strong WSW steering flow across SE GA produced a few strong wind gusts under stronger upper level dynamics.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down near Old Alma Road and West Horshoe Road. The time of damage was based on radar. The cost of damage was unknown, but it was estimated for inclusion in Storm Data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level storm system moved across the region overnight on April 22nd into 23rd. Abundant moisture and wind energy was in place to bring severe thunderstorms to the region. Damaging winds occurred along with some tornadoes. Flash flooding also occurred with efficient rainfall rates and heavy rainfall. As the cold front moved through the region later during the afternoon of the 23rd, a few more storms developed during peak daytime heating and brought some hail and damaging winds to portions of eastern Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down onto power lines in Gilbert.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A delayed report was received via social media of two center pivots blown over due to strong wind estimated at 80 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms moved south into Northwest Kansas during the evening.  Wind gusts up to 60 MPH were recorded as the storms moved through, with the strongest gust occurring near St. Francis.  Hail up to two inches in diameter fell with these storms, with the largest hail reported near Herndon.  As the storms moved south their intensity declined.

The drought status for these counties remained largely unchanged, except for the drought worsening to D3 for the far western part of Yuma County.  Heavy rainfall events occurred over the eastern parts of these counties, which lessened the drought over the eastern half.  Total precipitation for the month ranged from 0.35 to 6.44, with the departure from normal ranging from 2.67 below normal to 3.43 above normal.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The southwest corner of the county remained in D3 Drought, improving to D2 Drought over the western half, with the east half not in a drought.  Precipitation for the month ranged from 1.10 to 6.44.  The monthly precipitation ranged from 0.48 to 3.43 above normal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A diffuse surface trough axis was north of the Altamaha River basin with very high dew pts in the low/mid 70s across the entire forecast area south of the boundary. The 12z|JAX RAOB showed less deep layer moisture (PWAT 1.6 inches) and stronger SW steering flow across the entire area from 10-15 kts south of I-10 across NE FL to 20 kts across our SE GA zones. There was drier air in the low/mid levels where the steepest lapse rates were near 6.8 C/km between 790 mb and 617 mb roughly. SE GA 0-6 km bulk shear was 20-25 kts. Ingredients favored pulse strong to severe storms with gusty downburst winds the main hazard.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A home was struck by lightning near U.S. Highway 17 and Varney Road. A significant house fire occurred. The cost of damage was unknown but estimated for Storm Data.

An outbreak of severe weather occurred on Easter Sunday, 2020. This was a multifaceted event with a few different waves of activity, each of which brought their own unique hazardous weather to the residents of the region. This outbreak had a total of 20 tornadoes across the NWS Jackson service area. Of these, two tornadoes were long tracked and in excess of 60 miles. Additionally, the most intense tornado was historically significant as it was the widest tornado in Mississippi history at 2.25 miles and ranks as the third widest nationally. Unfortunately, fatalities occurred across the region, most of which came from the two long track tornadoes. Total fatalities were 14, which were across several counties and almost 100 people were injured. Of the 20 tornadoes, two were rated as EF4, one was an  EF3, four were EF2, ten were EF1 and there were three EF0.||The first wave of severe storms moved out of northeast Louisiana as a line of thunderstorms or QLCS. The bowing segment of this line was efficient at producing tornadoes as it moved across northeast Louisiana parishes and through central sections of Mississippi before tracking across Alabama. This part of the QLCS produced 13 tornadoes across the service area with the strongest being three EF2s that occurred west of Pioneer LA, northwest of Yazoo City MS, and north of Macon MS.||The next wave was focused around two large supercell storms where each produced long track tornadoes, and were the phenomena that had the greatest impact across south and southeast Mississippi. The first storm produced two EF4 tornadoes, one of which was on the ground for 68 miles before dissipating. This tornado was up to two miles wide in several locations, with the maximum width at 2.25 miles making it the widest tornado in Mississippi history. On the heels of this supercell, another supercell developed and produced a long track EF3 tornado, which was on the ground for 84 miles.||The third and final wave was associated with the southeast surge of the cold front and driven by the strong lift and winds from the core of the upper level low. This wave was a bit unique as there were not as many thunderstorms associated with the line of strong and damaging winds. However, this line of activity produced widespread wind damage across southeast Arkansas, northeast Louisiana and all of the northern half of Mississippi, including the Mississippi Delta where winds of 70 to 90 mph occurred. While many structures sustained some sort of damage, widespread trees and power lines were blown down during the late evening and early morning hours with the final wave.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A swath of wind caused damage from Duncan to Shaw. This included trees and power lines blown down across Duncan and Shelby. The most intense damage occurred from just Merigold to Shaw. In Merigold, around one dozen power poles were snapped along Crosby Road. A tree was also blown down onto a house in Merigold. Some limbs were blown down on the north side of Cleveland, but the worst damage occurred in and south of Cleveland. A wall collapsed at Parks Elementary School and the roof was blown off. Nearby trees were blown down. Trees were blown down along Memorial Drive and light poles were broken on US Highway 61. The tree damage around Cleveland was the worst in a two block wide corridor and some trees were blown down onto houses. Several trees were blown onto and damaged houses and vehicles in Boyle. Some shingles were lost on homes in the area and power lines were blown down. In Shaw, some small to large tree limbs were blown down and the north facing tin wall of an old mechanic shop was torn off.
